1
00:00:14,014 --> 00:00:17,550
These are the best chefs
for this return match. Come on out!

2
00:00:17,617 --> 00:00:18,618
SAM KIM & KWON SUNG-JUN

3
00:00:18,685 --> 00:00:19,853
Can you do this in 15 minutes?

4
00:00:19,919 --> 00:00:21,287
I don't think I can lose.

5
00:00:21,354 --> 00:00:22,756
-He doesn't think he can lose.
-He doesn't think he can lose.

6
00:00:22,822 --> 00:00:24,324
Please welcome today's fridge owners!

7
00:00:24,391 --> 00:00:25,992
TODAY'S FRIDGE OWNERS
LEE HEE-JUN, SONG JOONG-KI

8
00:00:26,059 --> 00:00:27,127
Chef Choi Hyun-suk

9
00:00:27,193 --> 00:00:29,429
-versus Webtoon Artist Kim Poong.
-I always had hand tremors.

10
00:00:29,496 --> 00:00:31,664
HOW WILL HE RESPOND?

11
00:00:31,731 --> 00:00:34,067
I never thought it could taste like this.

12
00:00:34,868 --> 00:00:36,536
HEE-JUN WAS MOVED BY FOOD
FOR THE FIRST TIME

13
00:00:36,603 --> 00:00:38,204
Chef Hyun-suk wins.

14
00:00:38,271 --> 00:00:39,639
CHOI HYUN-SUK WINS
AFTER MOVING HIS HEART

15
00:00:40,140 --> 00:00:43,176
The Master of Chinese Cuisine
and the Goddess of Chinese Cuisine.

16
00:00:43,243 --> 00:00:46,312
Hee-jun said he didn't enjoy Chinese food.

17
00:00:46,379 --> 00:00:49,616
It does feel unfamiliar.

18
00:00:49,682 --> 00:00:50,817
Which side?

19
00:00:50,884 --> 00:00:52,485
PARK EUN-YEONG WINS

20
00:00:52,552 --> 00:00:54,254
-A huge uproar will overtake the industry.
-I'm so sorry.

21
00:00:54,320 --> 00:00:56,156
Well, it was about time I retired.

22
00:00:56,222 --> 00:00:59,692
-No, you can't. No.
-Hee-jun made him retire!

23
00:01:00,293 --> 00:01:02,495
You're watching <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>.

24
00:01:02,562 --> 00:01:06,366
We're here today with Song Joong-ki
and Lee Hee-jun of <i>Bogotá</i>.

25
00:01:06,433 --> 00:01:09,102
Joong-ki's family recently had
such a happy occasion.

26
00:01:09,169 --> 00:01:10,437
HIS SECOND DAUGHTER WAS BORN
IN NOVEMBER 2024

27
00:01:10,503 --> 00:01:13,640
His second child was born
last year in November,

28
00:01:13,706 --> 00:01:15,442
a baby princess. Let's give him a hand.

29
00:01:15,508 --> 00:01:17,010
CONGRATULATIONS

30
00:01:17,577 --> 00:01:19,112
Does it feel real?

31
00:01:19,179 --> 00:01:21,614
It still hasn't hit me yet.

32
00:01:21,681 --> 00:01:25,385
It's been two weeks
since my second child was born.

33
00:01:26,853 --> 00:01:30,056
I'm just very happy. She's adorable.

34
00:01:30,123 --> 00:01:32,358
Your first child is a boy,
then your second is a girl.

35
00:01:32,425 --> 00:01:33,860
Yes, my firstborn. They're a year apart.

36
00:01:33,927 --> 00:01:38,364
And my daughter clung to me
more than the boy, and it felt so cozy.

37
00:01:38,431 --> 00:01:40,233
-That happens.
-Right?

38
00:01:40,300 --> 00:01:41,734
-It's not just me, is it?
-No.

39
00:01:41,801 --> 00:01:44,804
Both Sung-ju and I have
sons and daughters.

40
00:01:44,871 --> 00:01:46,473
Girls feel different in your arms.

41
00:01:46,539 --> 00:01:50,276
-I couldn't forget how she clung to me.
-You're right.

42
00:01:50,343 --> 00:01:53,480
-Does your son talk now? Right?
-He began to.

43
00:01:53,546 --> 00:01:55,815
Now that he's talking,
he's even more adorable.

44
00:01:55,882 --> 00:01:58,318
He'd go, "Daddy, good night."

45
00:01:58,384 --> 00:02:01,020
And even "I love you" in Korean.

46
00:02:01,087 --> 00:02:04,157
When he asks me to hold him,
he'll go, "<i>Collo</i>."

47
00:02:04,224 --> 00:02:07,460
<i>Collo</i> means neck in Italian,
so he's asking me to hold him here.

48
00:02:07,527 --> 00:02:09,429
-The neck area.
-The neck.

49
00:02:09,496 --> 00:02:12,465
My wife lives in Italy right now,

50
00:02:12,532 --> 00:02:14,467
so when my son began to talk,

51
00:02:14,534 --> 00:02:18,438
he talked in Italian,
and I couldn't understand.

52
00:02:18,505 --> 00:02:20,807
-I thought, "This is trouble."
-It can happen.

53
00:02:20,874 --> 00:02:23,476
I've been focused
on learning the language…

54
00:02:23,543 --> 00:02:25,512
-You should do that.
-…after my son was born.

55
00:02:25,578 --> 00:02:28,181
-That must be the case.
-On the other hand, my wife.

56
00:02:28,248 --> 00:02:31,584
Our son would sometimes say
Korean words that I taught him.

57
00:02:31,651 --> 00:02:34,754
So she's studying Korean.

58
00:02:34,821 --> 00:02:36,456
Do you talk to her in English?

59
00:02:36,523 --> 00:02:38,491
My wife and I talk in English.

60
00:02:38,558 --> 00:02:41,427
She speaks English, Italian,

61
00:02:41,494 --> 00:02:44,864
Spanish, and French.

62
00:02:44,931 --> 00:02:47,600
She's now learning to speak Korean,

63
00:02:47,667 --> 00:02:52,672
while I'm learning to speak
more English and Italian.

64
00:02:52,739 --> 00:02:55,441
From what we heard,

65
00:02:55,508 --> 00:03:00,513
you washed your baby for 200 days
without skipping a day.

66
00:03:00,580 --> 00:03:01,948
WHOA

67
00:03:02,015 --> 00:03:03,249
Is this true?

68
00:03:03,316 --> 00:03:06,719
Yes, I thought I should do that.

69
00:03:06,786 --> 00:03:09,022
-Because…
-It's not easy to bathe them every day.

70
00:03:09,088 --> 00:03:12,258
My mother taught me to do that
once my wife and I had a baby.

71
00:03:12,325 --> 00:03:15,061
And as I continued to do that,

72
00:03:15,128 --> 00:03:18,631
I began to enjoy
how my son looked straight at me.

73
00:03:19,232 --> 00:03:23,536
So, I'd bathe my son first
before I go to bed

74
00:03:23,603 --> 00:03:25,505
to feel like I spent a great day.

75
00:03:26,539 --> 00:03:28,541
Once he gets a little older,

76
00:03:28,608 --> 00:03:31,244
-you can draw a bath and go in together.
-Yes, right.

77
00:03:31,311 --> 00:03:34,214
-You two can bathe together.
-With his daddy.

78
00:03:34,280 --> 00:03:38,551
You'll choke up a little
when that happens.

79
00:03:38,618 --> 00:03:40,486
But once they grow up… Darn it.

80
00:03:40,553 --> 00:03:41,988
CHOKING UP BECAUSE OF HIS SON

81
00:03:42,055 --> 00:03:45,525
-Why, "Darn it"? It can happen.
-Is that so?

82
00:03:45,592 --> 00:03:49,195
Do you spend half the year in Italy?
Which area?

83
00:03:49,262 --> 00:03:51,130
We live in Toscana.

84
00:03:51,197 --> 00:03:54,400
When I work, I work in Korea,

85
00:03:54,467 --> 00:03:56,836
then I spend time with my family in Italy.

86
00:03:56,903 --> 00:03:59,038
Chef Sung-jun, didn't you study in Naples?

87
00:03:59,606 --> 00:04:02,742
I was here and there,
but I spent the most time in Naples.

88
00:04:02,809 --> 00:04:04,544
How far is it from Naples?

89
00:04:04,611 --> 00:04:07,080
Naples is south of Rome,

90
00:04:07,146 --> 00:04:10,783
but sadly, I haven't been to Naples yet.

91
00:04:10,850 --> 00:04:12,452
-I really want to.
-I see.

92
00:04:12,518 --> 00:04:14,887
I think you could go with me.

93
00:04:14,954 --> 00:04:16,623
HE SUDDENLY MAKES A MOVE

94
00:04:16,689 --> 00:04:18,925
-Let me be your guide.
-His guide?

95
00:04:18,992 --> 00:04:21,561
He's gotten a complete hold of Joong-ki.

96
00:04:21,628 --> 00:04:22,629
WHAT?

97
00:04:22,695 --> 00:04:25,698
I've always been a huge fan of Joong-ki.

98
00:04:25,765 --> 00:04:27,834
-You love the Eagles, right?
-Yes.

99
00:04:27,900 --> 00:04:30,737
I've also been a fan for 20 years now.

100
00:04:30,803 --> 00:04:34,107
-My gosh. Look at this.
-They support the same team.

101
00:04:34,173 --> 00:04:36,209
I suddenly feel very close to him.

102
00:04:38,311 --> 00:04:42,081
Was there something you wanted to do
with your children once they grew up?

103
00:04:42,148 --> 00:04:45,151
I had so many things,
including taking a bath, as you said,

104
00:04:45,218 --> 00:04:47,920
and playing my favorite sports,
like baseball, just as he said.

105
00:04:47,987 --> 00:04:51,824
I also want to go to a Hanhwa Eagles game
with them. There are so many things.

106
00:04:51,891 --> 00:04:54,093
-And dress them in the uniforms.
-Right.

107
00:04:54,160 --> 00:04:55,428
You have a son too, Hee-jun.

108
00:04:55,495 --> 00:04:57,764
-Yes, he's six years old.
-Six.

109
00:04:57,830 --> 00:05:02,035
Did you do anything
you hoped to do with him?

110
00:05:02,101 --> 00:05:06,239
I always dreamed of the moment
when he'd start

111
00:05:06,306 --> 00:05:08,741
riding a bicycle.

112
00:05:08,808 --> 00:05:11,411
<i>-The moment when you let him go.</i>
<i>-Yes, letting him go.</i>

113
00:05:11,477 --> 00:05:13,713
<i>-That's a thing.</i>
<i>-There's that moment.</i>

114
00:05:13,780 --> 00:05:16,883
I always told myself that
I'd be there for that moment.

115
00:05:16,949 --> 00:05:19,252
From the ages three to five,

116
00:05:19,319 --> 00:05:21,988
we continued to ride
a four-wheeled bike all the time.

117
00:05:22,055 --> 00:05:23,856
-We'd always do it together.
-You were there.

118
00:05:23,923 --> 00:05:27,427
Then, while I was gone shooting,
my wife took off the training wheels.

119
00:05:28,828 --> 00:05:30,997
-The training wheels?
-Yes, she took those off

120
00:05:31,064 --> 00:05:33,700
-and had that moment with our son.
-Gosh, I can't believe it.

121
00:05:33,766 --> 00:05:35,968
-That was such a dad moment.
-You waited for that.

122
00:05:36,035 --> 00:05:39,639
She took a picture of that and showed me,
and it was a huge bummer.

123
00:05:39,706 --> 00:05:41,274
Gosh, you should've been there.

124
00:05:41,341 --> 00:05:44,410
-When I trained him for three years.
-Right?

125
00:05:44,477 --> 00:05:46,979
He'll remember that
his mom helped him ride the bicycle.

126
00:05:47,046 --> 00:05:49,349
-He'll only remember that.
-And only that.

127
00:05:49,415 --> 00:05:50,483
What a shame.

128
00:05:50,550 --> 00:05:52,085
I'm learning a lot today.

129
00:05:52,151 --> 00:05:54,487
-You have to do that.
-Okay.

130
00:05:54,554 --> 00:05:58,091
Now, before we open up Joong-ki's fridge,

131
00:05:58,157 --> 00:06:00,827
let's decide on the contenders first.

132
00:06:00,893 --> 00:06:03,029
I wonder what his orders are.

133
00:06:03,096 --> 00:06:05,698
Let's find out his order. Show us!

134
00:06:05,765 --> 00:06:07,333
Joong-ki's orders.

135
00:06:07,400 --> 00:06:09,836
-"It's me, perilla oil."
-Perilla oil?

136
00:06:09,902 --> 00:06:11,904
"It's me, olive oil."

137
00:06:11,971 --> 00:06:14,574
-"It's me, perilla oil."
-We're using perilla oil?

138
00:06:14,640 --> 00:06:16,042
"It's me, perilla oil," was

139
00:06:16,109 --> 00:06:19,112
-something Chef Kang-rok said.
-Chef Kang-rok's words.

140
00:06:19,178 --> 00:06:21,147
-Olive oil?
-"It's me, olive oil"?

141
00:06:21,214 --> 00:06:23,049
Oil versus oil.

142
00:06:23,116 --> 00:06:26,185
Joong-ki, what are your orders?
Let's start with, "It's me, perilla oil."

143
00:06:26,252 --> 00:06:30,189
I live half of my time in Italy
and the other half in Korea.

144
00:06:30,256 --> 00:06:31,591
Perilla oil and olive oil.

145
00:06:31,657 --> 00:06:36,996
We use lots of sesame oil
or perilla oil to make Korean cuisine,

146
00:06:37,063 --> 00:06:40,032
-so I buy those in bulk when I go back.
-I see.

147
00:06:40,099 --> 00:06:42,735
And I've fallen
for Italian cuisine lately,

148
00:06:42,802 --> 00:06:46,072
so I always bring olive oil back to Korea.

149
00:06:46,139 --> 00:06:48,441
I also heard
that they're good for your health,

150
00:06:48,508 --> 00:06:50,343
so I have a spoonful of perilla oil

151
00:06:50,410 --> 00:06:53,246
or olive oil on an empty stomach
before breakfast.

152
00:06:53,312 --> 00:06:55,715
-It must be good for you.
-I heard it is.

153
00:06:55,782 --> 00:06:58,785
That was why I chose these ingredients.

154
00:06:58,851 --> 00:07:02,688
-"It's me, perilla oil" must be for him.
-Yes, for Chef Kang-rok.

155
00:07:02,755 --> 00:07:05,425
-It's you already.
-Can you say it for us?

156
00:07:05,491 --> 00:07:07,493
-It must be where he got it.
-You're right.

157
00:07:07,994 --> 00:07:09,729
It's me, perilla oil.

158
00:07:09,796 --> 00:07:11,397
-It was…
-Yes?

159
00:07:11,464 --> 00:07:14,434
…the simplest way

160
00:07:14,500 --> 00:07:17,036
of expressing the dish.

161
00:07:17,103 --> 00:07:19,105
It's me, perilla oil.

162
00:07:19,672 --> 00:07:21,541
HE GOT TO SEE
THAT MOVING LINE LIVE

163
00:07:21,607 --> 00:07:23,209
-That has a certain charm.
-Yes.

164
00:07:23,276 --> 00:07:25,812
Don't people around you
mention this often?

165
00:07:25,878 --> 00:07:28,448
They use these things to often tease me.

166
00:07:28,514 --> 00:07:30,950
The most shocking thing was,

167
00:07:31,017 --> 00:07:32,852
"It's me, face oil."

168
00:07:33,619 --> 00:07:35,254
Face oil was shocking?

169
00:07:35,321 --> 00:07:39,125
There are a few people
who want to tease me like that.

170
00:07:39,192 --> 00:07:42,795
Chef Kang-rok, you don't have a choice
but to choose that at this point.

171
00:07:42,862 --> 00:07:45,465
-Yes, I'll do the perilla oil.
-Perilla oil.

172
00:07:45,531 --> 00:07:47,066
A RERUN OF THE PERILLA OIL TOP DOG

173
00:07:47,133 --> 00:07:49,969
-He naturally takes place there.
-Yes, that's it.

174
00:07:50,036 --> 00:07:53,372
Chef Sung-jun, you naturally belong
with olive oil.

175
00:07:53,439 --> 00:07:54,474
-There's no one else.
-Yes.

176
00:07:54,540 --> 00:07:56,642
-Yes.
-You don't get to choose.

177
00:07:56,709 --> 00:07:59,111
-You're just going with olive oil.
-Of course.

178
00:07:59,178 --> 00:08:00,346
I'll also go for perilla oil.

179
00:08:00,413 --> 00:08:02,281
-Yes.
-He'll also go for perilla oil.

180
00:08:02,348 --> 00:08:04,417
After fighting him last week,

181
00:08:04,484 --> 00:08:07,553
for the next three battles,
I had a feeling that

182
00:08:07,620 --> 00:08:09,822
he'll be an easy fight.

183
00:08:09,889 --> 00:08:12,391
-He won the battle last week.
-An easy fight?

184
00:08:12,458 --> 00:08:14,760
So you can toy with him
at least three times.

185
00:08:14,827 --> 00:08:17,330
I feel more comfortable
using olive oil than perilla oil.

186
00:08:17,396 --> 00:08:18,698
-Of course.
-Right.

187
00:08:18,764 --> 00:08:19,966
Are you sure?

188
00:08:20,032 --> 00:08:23,636
-I think it'll be fun.
-Whoa.

189
00:08:23,703 --> 00:08:24,804
It's an honor.

190
00:08:24,871 --> 00:08:26,606
The unintentional big match.

191
00:08:26,672 --> 00:08:28,941
This was the best thing I did this year.

192
00:08:29,008 --> 00:08:30,643
Deciding to come to <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>.

193
00:08:30,710 --> 00:08:33,880
THANK YOU FOR SAYING THAT,
DEAR JOONG-KI

194
00:08:33,946 --> 00:08:36,115
-It's such an honor.
-Sure.

195
00:08:36,883 --> 00:08:37,917
COMING RIGHT UP

196
00:08:37,984 --> 00:08:40,186
<i>Who will become the best Italian chef?</i>

197
00:08:40,253 --> 00:08:42,922
<i>I'm going to win anyway. It'll be fun.</i>

198
00:08:42,989 --> 00:08:44,657
Oh, I can't watch this.

199
00:08:44,724 --> 00:08:46,459
It's impossible to do in 15 minutes.

200
00:08:46,526 --> 00:08:48,628
Let me ask you one last time.
Will the risotto be ready?

201
00:08:48,694 --> 00:08:50,096
Is it ready? Is it?

202
00:08:50,162 --> 00:08:51,764
Gosh, I can't watch this.

203
00:08:51,831 --> 00:08:53,099
WHO WILL WIN THE RISOTTO BATTLE?

204
00:08:54,500 --> 00:08:55,568
-I see.
-His face.

205
00:08:55,635 --> 00:08:57,236
It tastes insane.

206
00:08:57,803 --> 00:09:00,373
THE INSANE BATTLE
IS COMING RIGHT UP

207
00:09:00,439 --> 00:09:05,144
Let us go through Joong-ki's fridge
starting now.

208
00:09:05,211 --> 00:09:08,714
Is your wife okay with this?
Can we open it?

209
00:09:08,781 --> 00:09:11,384
-I told her about this.
-And?

210
00:09:11,450 --> 00:09:13,920
She told you to use everything freely.

211
00:09:13,986 --> 00:09:15,588
-Thank you.
-Okay.

212
00:09:15,655 --> 00:09:18,658
We present Joong-ki's fridge!

213
00:09:18,724 --> 00:09:21,227
SONG JOONG-KI'S FRIDGE IS
FINALLY PRESENTED

214
00:09:21,794 --> 00:09:24,030
-I see.
-Look at those.

215
00:09:24,096 --> 00:09:25,665
This side is the freezer,

216
00:09:25,731 --> 00:09:27,833
-and this must be the fridge.
-It's full.

217
00:09:27,900 --> 00:09:30,036
We're practically in Italy right now.

218
00:09:30,102 --> 00:09:32,271
IT'S LIKE WE'RE IN ITALY

219
00:09:32,338 --> 00:09:34,240
He has lots of sauces too.

220
00:09:34,307 --> 00:09:35,441
And wine.

221
00:09:35,508 --> 00:09:38,544
Now, the first row of the fridge.

222
00:09:38,611 --> 00:09:41,047
-It's gluten-free.
-Gluten-free?

223
00:09:41,113 --> 00:09:43,282
That's my wife's favorite.

224
00:09:43,349 --> 00:09:47,386
-She usually eats gluten-free food.
-She likes this one.

225
00:09:47,453 --> 00:09:49,922
-Is it for those who don't like flour?
-Right.

226
00:09:49,989 --> 00:09:52,158
It doesn't sit right with her.
She can't digest it.

227
00:09:52,224 --> 00:09:54,026
She likes it, but she has to hold back.

228
00:09:54,093 --> 00:09:55,828
I see. What's this?

229
00:09:55,895 --> 00:09:58,698
-That's rice-shaped pasta.
-That one. Yes.

230
00:09:58,764 --> 00:10:01,567
When we run out of gluten-free pasta,

231
00:10:01,634 --> 00:10:03,903
she always uses buckwheat.

232
00:10:03,970 --> 00:10:08,007
And she often uses it
to make our baby food.

233
00:10:08,074 --> 00:10:10,076
Do these help with her indigestion?

234
00:10:10,142 --> 00:10:11,744
It feels clean.

235
00:10:11,811 --> 00:10:15,314
Then it might be a good idea
to cook with these.

236
00:10:15,381 --> 00:10:16,716
What's this?

237
00:10:16,782 --> 00:10:19,018
-Rice to make risotto.
-Rice for risotto.

238
00:10:19,085 --> 00:10:22,722
Whenever I eat risotto,
the rice grains feel undercooked to me.

239
00:10:22,788 --> 00:10:23,889
Is that how it's cooked?

240
00:10:23,956 --> 00:10:27,727
That's the right method.
It's supposed to be <i>al dente</i>, undercooked.

241
00:10:27,793 --> 00:10:29,495
<i>The grains must retain the bite</i>

242
00:10:29,562 --> 00:10:32,365
<i>while the dish is runny, like porridge.</i>

243
00:10:32,431 --> 00:10:36,202
-That's risotto.
-And I see some canned food.

244
00:10:36,268 --> 00:10:38,871
-My favorite dish is <i>pasta al tonno</i>.
-<i>Tonno</i>?

245
00:10:38,938 --> 00:10:40,573
It means tuna.

246
00:10:40,640 --> 00:10:43,843
The servers always chuckle
whenever I order that at a restaurant.

247
00:10:43,909 --> 00:10:46,078
-Why?
-I asked my wife why,

248
00:10:46,145 --> 00:10:48,781
and she said tuna pasta is

249
00:10:48,848 --> 00:10:52,184
something many Italian kids
ask their mothers to make.

250
00:10:52,251 --> 00:10:53,352
So a kid's appetite.

251
00:10:53,419 --> 00:10:57,189
Older people tend to grow out
of their canned tuna phase.

252
00:10:57,256 --> 00:10:58,624
They have that stubbornness.

253
00:10:58,691 --> 00:11:01,193
They mostly want to eat fresh seafood.

254
00:11:01,260 --> 00:11:03,529
-Kids' appetite.
-So it's a dish for kids.

255
00:11:03,596 --> 00:11:05,398
This one must be cheese.

256
00:11:05,464 --> 00:11:07,500
Yes, that's parmigiano cheese.

257
00:11:07,566 --> 00:11:11,937
My wife sometimes grates that
and makes something.

258
00:11:12,004 --> 00:11:15,875
-The one in the bag was already grated.
-I see.

259
00:11:15,941 --> 00:11:19,812
The fridge feels so Italian.
I've never seen this before.

260
00:11:19,879 --> 00:11:21,614
What are these?

261
00:11:21,681 --> 00:11:22,882
<i>-Ham.</i>
<i>-Prosciutto.</i>

262
00:11:22,948 --> 00:11:25,284
<i>Prosciutto, salami, and whatnot.</i>

263
00:11:25,351 --> 00:11:29,021
It's easy to serve as starters
when we have guests.

264
00:11:29,088 --> 00:11:31,157
Can you get these in Korea?

265
00:11:31,223 --> 00:11:34,093
It's written in Korean,
so he must've bought it here.

266
00:11:35,261 --> 00:11:38,064
-Charcuterie…
-"Charcuterie"?

267
00:11:38,130 --> 00:11:41,634
-This is written in Korean too.
-"Dry-aged domestic pork shoulder,

268
00:11:41,701 --> 00:11:43,969
soft and savory charcuterie."

269
00:11:44,036 --> 00:11:45,971
Have you always enjoyed Western cuisine?

270
00:11:46,038 --> 00:11:47,540
Not at all.

271
00:11:47,606 --> 00:11:49,442
-Not at all.
-You weren't that type.

272
00:11:50,176 --> 00:11:53,345
I've never had
many Italian dishes in my life.

273
00:11:53,412 --> 00:11:54,413
UNFAMILIAR WITH ITALIAN CUISINE

274
00:11:54,480 --> 00:11:57,917
There's even a famous Italian restaurant

275
00:11:57,983 --> 00:11:59,819
named La Cucina in my neighborhood.

276
00:11:59,885 --> 00:12:02,421
-You used to work there.
-It was my first workplace.

277
00:12:02,488 --> 00:12:06,492
That was my first workplace,
and I stayed there for ten years.

278
00:12:07,927 --> 00:12:12,565
That was the first Italian restaurant
I dined at after moving to Seoul.

279
00:12:12,631 --> 00:12:14,467
-It's a famous place.
-Back then,

280
00:12:14,533 --> 00:12:16,335
I thought, "Why do people enjoy this?"

281
00:12:16,402 --> 00:12:18,304
although it was such a famous place.

282
00:12:18,370 --> 00:12:20,573
FEELING BITTER…

283
00:12:20,639 --> 00:12:22,775
Chef Hyun-suk was working there
at that time.

284
00:12:22,842 --> 00:12:25,211
He must've made his dishes.

285
00:12:25,277 --> 00:12:28,781
My taste in food until then
didn't know how to enjoy Italian food.

286
00:12:28,848 --> 00:12:31,250
-He held a prejudice.
-A stereotype.

287
00:12:31,317 --> 00:12:33,753
It was too simple and not too flavorful.

288
00:12:33,819 --> 00:12:37,423
-But these days, I'm very into it.
-I see.

289
00:12:37,490 --> 00:12:39,658
-Because your wife keeps cooking.
-Yes.

290
00:12:39,725 --> 00:12:40,893
-It's so good.
-He developed a taste.

291
00:12:40,960 --> 00:12:41,994
You weren't familiar with it.

292
00:12:42,061 --> 00:12:45,631
Then I went back to the same restaurant

293
00:12:45,698 --> 00:12:47,933
and finally realized how good it was.

294
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:50,569
He said it tasted great
after Chef Hyun-suk left.

295
00:12:50,636 --> 00:12:51,771
BECAUSE HYUN-SUK WASN'T THERE?

296
00:12:51,837 --> 00:12:55,074
Stop picking a fight.
That guy holds grudges.

297
00:12:55,141 --> 00:12:57,710
That was what Joong-ki said.

298
00:12:57,777 --> 00:13:00,079
He didn't enjoy it at first,
but he did later.

299
00:13:00,146 --> 00:13:01,614
FALLING APART

300
00:13:01,680 --> 00:13:06,152
We're seeing many ingredients
that your wife often uses.

301
00:13:06,218 --> 00:13:08,187
Is she a good cook too?

302
00:13:08,254 --> 00:13:09,288
-My wife?
-Yes.

303
00:13:09,355 --> 00:13:10,990
She is a good cook.

304
00:13:11,056 --> 00:13:13,292
She's also a Colombian,

305
00:13:13,359 --> 00:13:15,694
so she makes dishes from that country too.

306
00:13:15,761 --> 00:13:17,797
-My mother-in-law is Colombian.
-I see.

307
00:13:17,863 --> 00:13:21,901
She always makes turkey
at Christmas every year.

308
00:13:21,967 --> 00:13:23,903
She'd age the turkey and make it.

309
00:13:23,969 --> 00:13:27,506
And she recently learned how to make
Korean dishes and made them for me.

310
00:13:27,573 --> 00:13:32,077
I like dishes like abalone porridge
and bean sprouts and soy sauce bibimbap.

311
00:13:32,144 --> 00:13:34,146
She made those for me,
and it was delicious.

312
00:13:34,213 --> 00:13:36,649
Do you invite people home too?

313
00:13:36,715 --> 00:13:39,385
Yes, we love to do that.

314
00:13:39,451 --> 00:13:43,422
I lived in Budapest, Hungary
for about five months to shoot a movie,

315
00:13:43,489 --> 00:13:45,591
and my wife was there with me
at that time.

316
00:13:45,658 --> 00:13:49,795
She'd invite one team every week
and cooked for them.

317
00:13:49,862 --> 00:13:53,032
This week, the photography crew,
the next week, the lighting crew.

318
00:13:53,098 --> 00:13:54,500
That's not an easy thing to do.

319
00:13:54,567 --> 00:13:55,801
No, it really isn't.

320
00:13:55,868 --> 00:13:58,437
-Your wife?
-Yes, just like Hee-jun's wife,

321
00:13:58,504 --> 00:14:00,806
she likes to have guests
and cook Italian dishes.

322
00:14:00,873 --> 00:14:04,777
What was the most delicious Italian dish
you'd recommend people?

323
00:14:04,844 --> 00:14:08,581
Boars are called <i>cinghiale</i> in Italian.

324
00:14:08,647 --> 00:14:09,748
-Cinghiale.
-I have

325
00:14:09,815 --> 00:14:12,918
a neighbor named Mr. Aldo right next door.

326
00:14:12,985 --> 00:14:14,887
I mentioned it to him once,

327
00:14:14,954 --> 00:14:18,791
-and he made me <i>cinghiale</i> ragu pasta.
-Ragu?

328
00:14:18,858 --> 00:14:20,626
-That was the most delicious.
-A boar dish.

329
00:14:20,693 --> 00:14:22,394
It tastes great.

330
00:14:22,461 --> 00:14:25,798
-You still can't forget it.
-Mr. Aldo's ragu.

331
00:14:25,865 --> 00:14:29,635
-We should invite him some time.
-You're right.

332
00:14:29,702 --> 00:14:33,272
As we speak, I just spotted perilla oil.

333
00:14:33,339 --> 00:14:34,807
KEY INGREDIENT 7: PERILLA OIL

334
00:14:34,874 --> 00:14:36,408
I see perilla oil.

335
00:14:36,475 --> 00:14:39,211
The one in the soju bottle is
homemade by someone I know.

336
00:14:39,278 --> 00:14:40,279
This is perilla oil too.

337
00:14:40,346 --> 00:14:41,914
Yes, fresh from a mill.

338
00:14:41,981 --> 00:14:44,083
He has many types of perilla oil.

339
00:14:44,149 --> 00:14:45,784
You must love perilla oil.

340
00:14:45,851 --> 00:14:47,786
My wife's favorite is this.

341
00:14:47,853 --> 00:14:50,489
She asks me to grill tofu in perilla oil.

342
00:14:50,556 --> 00:14:52,358
-That's a good one.
-Yes.

343
00:14:52,424 --> 00:14:56,262
Right after she gave birth
to our second daughter in Italy,

344
00:14:56,328 --> 00:14:58,697
she immediately asked me
to grill some tofu in that oil.

345
00:14:58,764 --> 00:15:01,600
But it wasn't easy to find tofu in Rome.

346
00:15:01,667 --> 00:15:03,569
It was a bummer
that I couldn't do it for her.

347
00:15:03,636 --> 00:15:05,504
-But she loves that.
-I see.

348
00:15:05,571 --> 00:15:07,640
You two are
working out each other's appetites.

349
00:15:07,706 --> 00:15:09,275
-Yes.
-She loves it.

350
00:15:09,341 --> 00:15:12,478
I also see some Korean side dishes.

351
00:15:12,544 --> 00:15:15,314
Kimchi. I see cucumber kimchi too.

352
00:15:15,381 --> 00:15:18,050
-You're right.
-And pickled garlic cloves.

353
00:15:18,117 --> 00:15:20,252
-My mother made those.
-Your mother.

354
00:15:20,319 --> 00:15:22,288
Seasoned perilla leaves
made by his mother.

355
00:15:22,354 --> 00:15:23,889
It's seasoned in soy sauce.

356
00:15:23,956 --> 00:15:26,458
<i>Soy sauce. Oh, soy sauce and doenjang.</i>

357
00:15:26,525 --> 00:15:27,526
<i>Two flavors of perilla leaves.</i>

358
00:15:27,593 --> 00:15:30,262
And now, the freezer.

359
00:15:30,329 --> 00:15:33,599
<i>-Korean beef.</i>
<i>-Top-grade Korean beef, strip loin.</i>

360
00:15:33,666 --> 00:15:36,101
<i>Is that beef brisket? I see some of that.</i>

361
00:15:36,168 --> 00:15:38,170
Do you prefer red meat to seafood?

362
00:15:38,237 --> 00:15:41,607
-I do prefer red meat to seafood.
-I see.

363
00:15:41,674 --> 00:15:43,776
You're different from Hee-jun.

364
00:15:43,842 --> 00:15:45,544
What are these?

365
00:15:45,611 --> 00:15:47,279
<i>Porcini.</i>

366
00:15:47,346 --> 00:15:50,316
-I see sunflower seeds and almonds.
-Yes.

367
00:15:50,382 --> 00:15:52,751
-Some peanuts too.
-Yes.

368
00:15:52,818 --> 00:15:55,854
-What about these? Lentils?
-Lentils.

369
00:15:55,921 --> 00:15:58,657
My wife cooks with that
at least once a week.

370
00:15:58,724 --> 00:16:00,960
She boils lentils with lamb.

371
00:16:01,026 --> 00:16:03,295
-I see.
-She boils lentils with lamb?

372
00:16:03,362 --> 00:16:06,131
-She makes it when I must lose weight.
-Right.

373
00:16:06,198 --> 00:16:08,500
-There are some fish.
-There still are some fish.

374
00:16:08,567 --> 00:16:11,437
-Look at those.
-He has many different types.

375
00:16:11,503 --> 00:16:12,504
Halibut.

376
00:16:12,571 --> 00:16:14,506
When I have to lose weight,

377
00:16:14,573 --> 00:16:18,677
it's the easiest
to pop those into an air fryer.

378
00:16:18,744 --> 00:16:21,246
And they'll need olive oil.

379
00:16:21,313 --> 00:16:23,482
-There they are.
-Yes.

380
00:16:23,549 --> 00:16:28,020
We take pride
in the olive oil we use, actually.

381
00:16:28,087 --> 00:16:32,224
The olive oil we used when we're in Italy

382
00:16:32,291 --> 00:16:37,262
-comes straight from a tree in our home.
-Really?

383
00:16:37,329 --> 00:16:39,565
WHOA, THAT'S AMAZING

384
00:16:39,631 --> 00:16:42,334
-So you have olive trees?
-Yes, a few.

385
00:16:42,401 --> 00:16:44,636
Two months ago, we harvested everything

386
00:16:44,703 --> 00:16:46,638
and had Mr. Aldo next door
extract them for us.

387
00:16:46,705 --> 00:16:48,874
-Mr. Aldo again.
-I wonder what he's like.

388
00:16:48,941 --> 00:16:51,410
-He should visit us sometime.
-We should visit him.

389
00:16:51,477 --> 00:16:55,681
There are mills where people come
to extract olive oil, just like Korea.

390
00:16:55,748 --> 00:16:58,183
But because it's straight from our tree,

391
00:16:58,250 --> 00:17:01,487
so it feels satisfying and heartwarming
all around the year.

392
00:17:01,553 --> 00:17:02,821
He must feel more attached.

393
00:17:02,888 --> 00:17:06,158
That was all
for the ingredients in Joong-ki's fridge.

394
00:17:06,225 --> 00:17:09,028
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

395
00:17:09,094 --> 00:17:10,596
THE COOK-OFF BEGINS NOW

396
00:17:10,662 --> 00:17:12,064
We're starting now.

397
00:17:12,131 --> 00:17:16,035
This is the first round
with ingredients from Joong-ki's fridge.

398
00:17:16,101 --> 00:17:18,737
In the year 2024,

399
00:17:18,804 --> 00:17:21,440
Chef Kang-rok had lost
against Chef Ho-young.

400
00:17:21,507 --> 00:17:24,977
This is a revenge match for you,
Chef Kang-rok.

401
00:17:25,044 --> 00:17:28,247
If you lose twice in a row,
even viewers will think

402
00:17:28,313 --> 00:17:30,849
that Chef Ho-young must have
better skills.

403
00:17:30,916 --> 00:17:33,652
Well, can't you go easy on me
until the third time?

404
00:17:33,719 --> 00:17:36,955
-We need to give him three chances.
-Right.

405
00:17:37,022 --> 00:17:40,359
-May I give him a tip as his team leader?
-Yes, sure.

406
00:17:40,426 --> 00:17:42,694
Chef Kang-rok, you prep everything first,

407
00:17:42,761 --> 00:17:45,898
and the actual cooking time is very short
before you serve it, right?

408
00:17:45,964 --> 00:17:47,900
Think of three minutes
as your cooking time

409
00:17:47,966 --> 00:17:50,369
and just spend 12 minutes prepping.

410
00:17:50,436 --> 00:17:52,738
I know you can do it.

411
00:17:52,805 --> 00:17:54,373
Was that helpful?

412
00:17:54,440 --> 00:17:56,308
Yes. Thanks.

413
00:17:57,342 --> 00:17:58,477
Thanks.

414
00:18:00,212 --> 00:18:02,214
He didn't mean that.

415
00:18:02,281 --> 00:18:04,183
He was like, "I'll manage."

416
00:18:04,249 --> 00:18:05,584
HE WASN'T TOO HELPFUL

417
00:18:05,651 --> 00:18:08,220
-He has his appeal.
-He's like, "Whatever."

418
00:18:08,287 --> 00:18:09,855
It'd be nice if he did this in my place.

419
00:18:10,923 --> 00:18:13,258
-Doing this in his place.
-"Or do it for me!"

420
00:18:13,325 --> 00:18:15,794
-"You do it!"
-He'll have to handle it anyway.

421
00:18:15,861 --> 00:18:16,995
-In the end…
-That's what it is.

422
00:18:17,062 --> 00:18:18,564
…even my team attacked me.

423
00:18:20,899 --> 00:18:22,000
I WAS JOKING, LEADER

424
00:18:22,067 --> 00:18:25,604
-We let you use your perks last time.
-We did.

425
00:18:25,671 --> 00:18:27,973
But you competed without it.

426
00:18:28,040 --> 00:18:29,408
Do you plan to skip it again?

427
00:18:29,475 --> 00:18:32,611
I want to use it today.

428
00:18:32,678 --> 00:18:34,012
You do?

429
00:18:34,079 --> 00:18:35,881
He's in shock.

430
00:18:35,948 --> 00:18:37,449
It's better to use it.

431
00:18:37,516 --> 00:18:39,451
-I thought I should use it.
-Right?

432
00:18:39,518 --> 00:18:41,386
I'll use it later. I'll stop him.

433
00:18:41,453 --> 00:18:42,521
-One-minute stop.
-Yes.

434
00:18:42,588 --> 00:18:44,790
You'll stop him for a minute
during the cook-off.

435
00:18:44,857 --> 00:18:46,925
In that case, may I suggest a way

436
00:18:46,992 --> 00:18:50,796
for Chef Ho-young
to put Chef Kang-rok under confusion?

437
00:18:50,863 --> 00:18:52,331
What should I do?

438
00:18:52,397 --> 00:18:55,434
Why don't you do the salsa dance
and confuse him for a minute?

439
00:18:56,068 --> 00:18:58,804
LAST WEEK, HE DID THE SALSA DANCE

440
00:18:59,438 --> 00:19:01,406
Is that all right with you?

441
00:19:01,974 --> 00:19:05,410
I tried my best
to cook elegantly throughout my life.

442
00:19:07,513 --> 00:19:08,514
"Elegantly."

443
00:19:08,580 --> 00:19:12,351
-I did my best to stay composed.
-I see.

444
00:19:12,417 --> 00:19:13,652
The salsa dance?

445
00:19:14,887 --> 00:19:15,988
The salsa dance?

446
00:19:16,054 --> 00:19:17,422
THE ELEGANT MAN FACES A DANGER

447
00:19:17,489 --> 00:19:18,857
"The salsa dance?"

448
00:19:18,924 --> 00:19:22,928
-He's condemning the hosts elegantly.
-He is.

449
00:19:22,995 --> 00:19:24,530
"The salsa dance?"

450
00:19:24,596 --> 00:19:27,399
If you find him too irritating,

451
00:19:27,466 --> 00:19:28,700
then dance with him.

452
00:19:28,767 --> 00:19:30,002
AN OFFER FOR A SALSA DANCE-OFF!

453
00:19:30,068 --> 00:19:32,504
-You can do that.
-Dance with him?

454
00:19:32,571 --> 00:19:34,273
Was he not like that in school?

455
00:19:35,007 --> 00:19:36,074
No, he was taciturn.

456
00:19:36,141 --> 00:19:38,043
<i>I see. He was taciturn.</i>

457
00:19:38,110 --> 00:19:40,212
THE TACITURN UPPERCLASSMAN

458
00:19:40,279 --> 00:19:42,314
-The salsa dance?
-"The salsa dance?"

459
00:19:42,381 --> 00:19:43,715
SHAKING HEAD

460
00:19:43,782 --> 00:19:45,484
"The salsa dance?"

461
00:19:45,551 --> 00:19:47,586
That charismatic guy is
doing the salsa dance?

462
00:19:47,653 --> 00:19:49,221
-"The salsa dance?"
-"The salsa dance?"

463
00:19:50,522 --> 00:19:52,257
-He has compromised with the world.
-Yes.

464
00:19:53,192 --> 00:19:54,259
CHEF HO-YOUNG'S INGREDIENTS:
CANNED TUNA,

465
00:19:54,326 --> 00:19:55,427
SHABU-SHABU BROTH,
SEASONED PERILLA LEAVES

466
00:19:55,494 --> 00:19:56,695
AVOCADO, RAW PERILLA OIL,
PERILLA OIL, CUCUMBER KIMCHI

467
00:19:56,762 --> 00:19:57,829
TOFU, SEAWEED,
BUCKWHEAT NOODLES, HALIBUT

468
00:19:57,896 --> 00:20:00,332
CHEF KANG-ROK'S INGREDIENTS:
PARMIGIANO REGGIANO CHEESE

469
00:20:00,399 --> 00:20:01,533
SHABU-SHABU MEAT,
MOZZARELLA CHEESE,

470
00:20:01,600 --> 00:20:02,834
PERILLA OIL, WHITE WINE,
RAW PERILLA OIL

471
00:20:02,901 --> 00:20:05,037
Chef Kang-rok, what's your dish?

472
00:20:05,103 --> 00:20:09,208
I've already said
"It's me, perilla oil" before.

473
00:20:09,274 --> 00:20:13,278
So my dish is called,
"It's Me Again, Perilla Oil."

474
00:20:13,345 --> 00:20:16,048
-"It's Me Again, Perilla Oil."
-"It's Me Again, Perilla Oil."

475
00:20:16,114 --> 00:20:17,816
-That's charming.
-"It's Me Again, Perilla Oil."

476
00:20:17,883 --> 00:20:19,751
