-Very much.

955
00:39:50,521 --> 00:39:52,957
It only has her favorite ingredients.

956
00:39:53,023 --> 00:39:54,792
Were the noodles cooked all right?

957
00:39:54,859 --> 00:39:56,994
I didn't think it was overcooked.

958
00:39:57,061 --> 00:39:59,230
I like how sticky it felt, actually.

959
00:39:59,797 --> 00:40:01,065
That's a relief.

960
00:40:01,632 --> 00:40:03,501
PERILLA OIL BEEF TARTARE
WITH SABAYON

961
00:40:04,769 --> 00:40:07,138
BULGOGI-FLAVORED
PERILLA OIL FRITTATA

962
00:40:07,705 --> 00:40:12,076
CHEF CHOI KANG-ROK'S
IT'S ME AGAIN, PERILLA OIL

963
00:40:12,643 --> 00:40:14,378
Toward the end of the round,

964
00:40:14,445 --> 00:40:17,848
I heard Chef Kang-rok say, "I'm done for."

965
00:40:17,915 --> 00:40:18,916
I'm done for.

966
00:40:18,983 --> 00:40:21,986
-You said it quietly, but I heard it.
-He said he was done for.

967
00:40:22,052 --> 00:40:25,322
-He ran out of time.
-I hope the inside was cooked.

968
00:40:25,389 --> 00:40:27,224
Is it fully cooked?

969
00:40:27,291 --> 00:40:29,460
Should he try the beef tartare first?

970
00:40:29,527 --> 00:40:31,028
-Yes.
-The appetizer.

971
00:40:31,095 --> 00:40:34,899
He made two servings to remind you
of dining with your wife.

972
00:40:34,965 --> 00:40:36,467
I made it with raw perilla oil.

973
00:40:36,534 --> 00:40:39,904
-Raw perilla oil?
-I poured it on the dish first.

974
00:40:39,970 --> 00:40:41,939
-It doesn't smell too strong.
-No.

975
00:40:42,006 --> 00:40:44,775
-You can dip it lightly in the oil.
-It smells more subtle.

976
00:40:45,342 --> 00:40:48,712
I wonder if perilla oil
and cheese will mix well.

977
00:40:48,779 --> 00:40:51,449
-Will perilla oil go with cheese?
-I'm curious.

978
00:40:52,116 --> 00:40:53,350
HOW'S THE PERILLA OIL BEEF TARTARE?

979
00:40:53,417 --> 00:40:56,454
Now, he had the appetizer.

980
00:40:57,721 --> 00:40:58,722
NERVOUS

981
00:40:59,490 --> 00:41:00,891
The smell of the perilla oil just hit me.

982
00:41:02,359 --> 00:41:05,129
I can smell it from this far.

983
00:41:05,196 --> 00:41:06,964
This is it.

984
00:41:07,031 --> 00:41:08,666
The Italian omelet.

985
00:41:08,732 --> 00:41:10,134
Frittata.

986
00:41:10,201 --> 00:41:11,335
LOOKS

987
00:41:11,402 --> 00:41:12,937
-It was cooked well.
-I see.

988
00:41:13,437 --> 00:41:16,006
-Was it fully cooked?
-I think so.

989
00:41:18,976 --> 00:41:20,177
HE TAKES A BIG BITE

990
00:41:20,244 --> 00:41:21,846
YUM!

991
00:41:21,912 --> 00:41:23,113
He just had a bite.

992
00:41:25,416 --> 00:41:26,951
SAVORING

993
00:41:27,017 --> 00:41:29,119
I wonder what it'll taste like.

994
00:41:29,186 --> 00:41:32,223
-It looks good.
-What?

995
00:41:32,289 --> 00:41:33,657
Let me have one more bite.

996
00:41:33,724 --> 00:41:36,527
The parmigiano must've worked
as the seasoning.

997
00:41:37,294 --> 00:41:39,363
I wonder
if it'll go well with perilla oil.

998
00:41:39,430 --> 00:41:41,966
Will it smell like perilla oil at all?

999
00:41:42,032 --> 00:41:44,335
-Was it fully cooked?
-It was.

1000
00:41:44,401 --> 00:41:47,838
Throwing in onion was an excellent idea.

1001
00:41:47,905 --> 00:41:49,340
-The onion.
-The onion.

1002
00:41:49,406 --> 00:41:53,410
The meat was so soft that
it was a shame how it disappeared so fast.

1003
00:41:53,477 --> 00:41:57,414
-But the onion adds a bit of crunch.
-The texture is important too.

1004
00:41:57,481 --> 00:41:59,650
My wife would love this.

1005
00:41:59,717 --> 00:42:04,288
-But she'd like… Yes, this beef tartare.
-The beef tartare.

1006
00:42:04,355 --> 00:42:06,390
-Yes, thank you very much.
-Sure.

1007
00:42:07,491 --> 00:42:08,492
All right.

1008
00:42:08,559 --> 00:42:10,027
Why don't we have a bite too?

1009
00:42:10,094 --> 00:42:14,999
Let's try Chef Ho-young's HIP first.

1010
00:42:15,065 --> 00:42:16,066
HIP.

1011
00:42:16,133 --> 00:42:17,201
YUM

1012
00:42:18,836 --> 00:42:21,138
The perilla oil smell is quite strong.

1013
00:42:22,239 --> 00:42:24,174
I thought you'd like it.

1014
00:42:24,241 --> 00:42:28,646
These were 100% buckwheat noodles,
so we couldn't say these were overcooked.

1015
00:42:28,712 --> 00:42:30,848
When I bite on the cucumber,

1016
00:42:30,915 --> 00:42:34,318
it tastes crunchy and a bit salty too,

1017
00:42:34,385 --> 00:42:36,186
changing the flavor a little.
It's delicious.

1018
00:42:36,253 --> 00:42:37,621
THE FILLINGS MIX WELL

1019
00:42:37,688 --> 00:42:39,790
-The buckwheat <i>gimbap</i> was so good.
-Right?

1020
00:42:39,857 --> 00:42:43,460
The perilla oil scent spreads nicely,
and I love the sauce too.

1021
00:42:43,527 --> 00:42:45,930
I'd line up to buy this.

1022
00:42:47,231 --> 00:42:49,266
-You'd line up for this?
-Right here?

1023
00:42:49,333 --> 00:42:51,402
-You must like this clean taste.
-Yes.

1024
00:42:53,070 --> 00:42:54,071
I didn't know.

1025
00:42:54,138 --> 00:42:56,740
Next, Chef Kang-rok's dishes.

1026
00:42:56,807 --> 00:42:58,208
It's Me Again, Perilla Oil.

1027
00:42:58,275 --> 00:42:59,510
It tastes very classy.

1028
00:42:59,577 --> 00:43:01,845
Gosh, this is good.

1029
00:43:01,912 --> 00:43:03,347
It goes well with the beefy flavor.

1030
00:43:03,414 --> 00:43:05,649
-This is good too.
-It is.

1031
00:43:05,716 --> 00:43:06,917
It's good.

1032
00:43:06,984 --> 00:43:09,253
-It's sweet and sour.
-Right?

1033
00:43:09,320 --> 00:43:12,823
I even want to mix rice in this.
It'd be delicious like that.

1034
00:43:12,890 --> 00:43:16,093
It sounds awful
when you say bulgogi tastes sour,

1035
00:43:16,160 --> 00:43:20,264
but that bit of tart flavor
made it taste much fresher.

1036
00:43:20,331 --> 00:43:22,032
-It tastes familiar.
-It wasn't so bad.

1037
00:43:22,099 --> 00:43:23,434
What's the sour taste?

1038
00:43:23,500 --> 00:43:25,336
I added Italian wine.

1039
00:43:25,402 --> 00:43:29,239
-From the fridge?
-He had leftover wine in the fridge.

1040
00:43:29,306 --> 00:43:31,942
I threw in the leftover wine.

1041
00:43:32,009 --> 00:43:35,679
That was something I used to cook.

1042
00:43:35,746 --> 00:43:36,847
Did you put that in?

1043
00:43:36,914 --> 00:43:40,084
-Yes.
-That was the sour flavor.

1044
00:43:40,150 --> 00:43:41,785
Did the salsa dance confuse you?

1045
00:43:41,852 --> 00:43:43,554
Well, he was free to dance.

1046
00:43:43,621 --> 00:43:47,057
-But I didn't think he could come over.
-No.

1047
00:43:47,124 --> 00:43:48,258
EMBARRASSED

1048
00:43:48,325 --> 00:43:51,862
Everyone is smiling except for Joong-ki.

1049
00:43:51,929 --> 00:43:53,330
-It's hard.
-It is.

1050
00:43:53,397 --> 00:43:55,099
Who will he choose?

1051
00:43:55,165 --> 00:43:57,434
Number one is Jung Ho-young,

1052
00:43:57,501 --> 00:43:59,470
and number two, Choi Kang-rok.

1053
00:43:59,536 --> 00:44:02,106
Which one captured your appetite?
Please make your decision.

1054
00:44:02,172 --> 00:44:04,041
Please press the button!

1055
00:44:04,108 --> 00:44:06,577
-Gosh.
-My gosh.

1056
00:44:06,644 --> 00:44:08,178
So this is how it feels.

1057
00:44:09,179 --> 00:44:11,048
-I pressed it.
-You did.

1058
00:44:11,115 --> 00:44:13,951
Let's find out which one he chose.

1059
00:44:14,018 --> 00:44:17,454
Who did he choose? Here's the result.

1060
00:44:17,521 --> 00:44:19,089
Please show us!

1061
00:44:19,156 --> 00:44:20,324
It's me, perilla oil.

1062
00:44:20,391 --> 00:44:22,926
This was Jung Ho-young
and Choi Kang-rok's return match.

1063
00:44:22,993 --> 00:44:25,696
The two are alumni.

1064
00:44:25,763 --> 00:44:26,897
Will it be Jung Ho-young?

1065
00:44:26,964 --> 00:44:28,132
Or Choi Kang-rok?

1066
00:44:28,198 --> 00:44:31,035
Who did Joong-ki choose?

1067
00:44:31,735 --> 00:44:33,470
The winner is…

1068
00:44:33,537 --> 00:44:35,305
JUNG HO-YOUNG WINS

1069
00:44:35,372 --> 00:44:36,440
The winner is…

1070
00:44:36,507 --> 00:44:38,342
JUNG HO-YOUNG'S HIP WINS

1071
00:44:38,409 --> 00:44:40,444
Chef Ho-young wins again.

1072
00:44:41,445 --> 00:44:44,915
Joong-ki picks Chef Ho-young.

1073
00:44:44,982 --> 00:44:46,583
-The salsa dance?
-Yes.

1074
00:44:46,650 --> 00:44:49,119
But Chef Kang-rok's dishes were
delicious too.

1075
00:44:49,186 --> 00:44:50,888
-I loved these.
-Yes.

1076
00:44:50,954 --> 00:44:52,856
Why did you choose Chef Ho-young?

1077
00:44:52,923 --> 00:44:56,927
Both dishes were delicious,
so it was tough to choose.

1078
00:44:56,994 --> 00:44:58,028
But the salsa dance was big.

1079
00:44:59,663 --> 00:45:01,832
-The salsa dance.
-I see.

1080
00:45:03,434 --> 00:45:05,369
I told you that you could join him.

1081
00:45:07,104 --> 00:45:10,741
The dishes were both great,
but the salsa dance added points.

1082
00:45:10,808 --> 00:45:14,645
Gosh, is Chef Kang-rok
unable to surpass Chef Ho-young?

1083
00:45:14,712 --> 00:45:18,048
-Please give me three chances.
-Three chances.

1084
00:45:18,115 --> 00:45:21,452
Then we'll keep our eyes on this
until the third time.

1085
00:45:21,518 --> 00:45:24,855
Chef Ho-young is the winner.
Please come and get your star.

1086
00:45:25,723 --> 00:45:27,891
This was his second victory!

1087
00:45:27,958 --> 00:45:30,627
Congratulations! Chef Ho-young wins.

1088
00:45:31,428 --> 00:45:36,266
HIP BY CHEF JUNG HO-YOUNG:
THE RECIPE

1089
00:45:36,900 --> 00:45:37,901
GETTING READY FOR ROUND 2

1090
00:45:37,968 --> 00:45:39,737
It really is confusing.

1091
00:45:39,803 --> 00:45:42,806
-I haven't seen Sam cook for so long.
-Right?

1092
00:45:43,640 --> 00:45:45,809
IT'S BEEN SO LONG, SO HE'S NERVOUS

1093
00:45:46,577 --> 00:45:48,045
ON THE OTHER HAND

1094
00:45:48,912 --> 00:45:51,381
-Sung-jun doesn't get nervous.
-No.

1095
00:45:51,448 --> 00:45:54,318
-The two have switched.
-I can keep it open, right?

1096
00:45:55,052 --> 00:45:57,521
Sung-jun.

1097
00:45:57,588 --> 00:45:59,556
YOUR NAME TAG IS CROOKED

1098
00:46:00,824 --> 00:46:03,327
The crooked name tag is a bad sign.

1099
00:46:05,062 --> 00:46:06,497
That happened to me before.

1100
00:46:06,563 --> 00:46:08,599
I LOST BECAUSE OF
THE CROOKED NAME TAG

1101
00:46:08,665 --> 00:46:12,669
This next round is
a battle between two Italian chefs.

1102
00:46:12,736 --> 00:46:14,404
Italian chef, Sam Kim versus

1103
00:46:14,471 --> 00:46:17,141
the winner of <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>,
known as Napoli Matfia,

1104
00:46:17,207 --> 00:46:20,544
Chef Kwon Sung-jun.

1105
00:46:20,611 --> 00:46:22,946
I'm looking forward to this.

1106
00:46:23,013 --> 00:46:25,315
I didn't expect to see a battle like this.

1107
00:46:25,382 --> 00:46:26,917
Look at his face.

1108
00:46:26,984 --> 00:46:28,652
He looks so confident.

1109
00:46:29,219 --> 00:46:30,654
Am I like him too?

1110
00:46:32,356 --> 00:46:35,459
-He's walking in our shoes.
-He needed that.

1111
00:46:35,526 --> 00:46:37,494
It's your first 15-minute cook-off.
Can you do this?

1112
00:46:37,561 --> 00:46:39,897
Yes, of course, I am.

1113
00:46:40,464 --> 00:46:41,632
OY, THIS IS WHAT WE CALL VIGOR

1114
00:46:41,698 --> 00:46:43,400
"Of course, I am."

1115
00:46:43,467 --> 00:46:47,271
Last time, Chef Edward,
the second place of <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>,

1116
00:46:47,337 --> 00:46:49,239
got destroyed on his first try.

1117
00:46:49,306 --> 00:46:52,276
That doesn't have anything to do
with the first place.

1118
00:46:53,177 --> 00:46:54,311
Whoa.

1119
00:46:54,378 --> 00:46:57,314
-He owned that.
-I see.

1120
00:46:57,381 --> 00:47:00,450
-He was in second place.
-It has nothing to do with the first.

1121
00:47:00,517 --> 00:47:03,453
But you're up against Sam Kim.
Are you sure you'll win?

1122
00:47:03,520 --> 00:47:05,889
It doesn't matter who I'm up against.

1123
00:47:05,956 --> 00:47:08,025
I'm going to win anyway.

1124
00:47:09,393 --> 00:47:11,895
He's like a copy of you.
You two are the same!

1125
00:47:11,962 --> 00:47:13,630
You two have the same way of talking.

1126
00:47:13,697 --> 00:47:15,599
You're cool.

1127
00:47:15,666 --> 00:47:17,835
When did you begin your career, Chef Sam?

1128
00:47:17,901 --> 00:47:19,603
I was around 23.

1129
00:47:19,670 --> 00:47:21,872
When you first began to cook,

1130
00:47:21,939 --> 00:47:24,241
Chef Sung-jun was five.

1131
00:47:24,308 --> 00:47:26,410
BORN IN 1995, BORN IN 1977

1132
00:47:26,476 --> 00:47:29,847
When he began to eat rice,
Chef Sam was making pasta.

1133
00:47:29,913 --> 00:47:32,649
My first memory of cooking something was

1134
00:47:32,716 --> 00:47:33,817
when I was six years old.

1135
00:47:33,884 --> 00:47:36,386
What is he saying now?

1136
00:47:36,954 --> 00:47:38,655
What's he saying?

1137
00:47:38,722 --> 00:47:42,025
-I remember making fried rice at six.
-Fried rice.

1138
00:47:42,092 --> 00:47:43,961
He's worse than me.

1139
00:47:45,696 --> 00:47:47,764
Sam, why did you start so late?

1140
00:47:48,298 --> 00:47:50,500
Why did you start that late?

1141
00:47:50,567 --> 00:47:52,502
What were you doing at six?

1142
00:47:52,569 --> 00:47:55,372
I have a special suggestion to make.

1143
00:47:55,439 --> 00:47:56,974
Why don't we give the perk to Sam?

1144
00:47:57,040 --> 00:47:59,309
We'd love to do that.

1145
00:47:59,376 --> 00:48:02,079
The air in here seems like
Sam can use the perk.

1146
00:48:02,145 --> 00:48:05,115
I think Chef Sung-jun will
accept the offer.

1147
00:48:05,182 --> 00:48:07,751
The leader of the new chefs suggested

1148
00:48:07,818 --> 00:48:11,655
-that Sam took the perk.
-And switch it around?

1149
00:48:11,722 --> 00:48:13,190
He looks that confident.

1150
00:48:13,257 --> 00:48:15,025
Sam, is that okay?
Doesn't it kill your pride?

1151
00:48:15,092 --> 00:48:16,727
Doesn't it kill your pride? Is that okay?

1152
00:48:16,793 --> 00:48:17,895
It does.

1153
00:48:19,730 --> 00:48:22,432
But if he gives it up,
will you accept it or not?

1154
00:48:22,499 --> 00:48:23,600
I will.

1155
00:48:24,768 --> 00:48:25,903
I will.

1156
00:48:25,969 --> 00:48:27,804
GIVE ME THE PERK, PLEASE

1157
00:48:29,973 --> 00:48:31,108
PICKING PRACTICALITY OVER PRIDE

1158
00:48:31,174 --> 00:48:33,777
-It kills his pride, but he'll take it.
-He'll take it.

1159
00:48:33,844 --> 00:48:35,212
It sounds like a great idea.

1160
00:48:35,779 --> 00:48:37,547
-But I have to win today.
-I see.

1161
00:48:37,614 --> 00:48:39,216
I'll use it myself.

1162
00:48:40,751 --> 00:48:42,452
Sam ended up only looking ridiculous.

1163
00:48:43,020 --> 00:48:44,421
IF HE DECLINED,
HE COULD'VE LOOKED COOL

1164
00:48:44,488 --> 00:48:46,390
He should've said no.

1165
00:48:46,456 --> 00:48:49,092
-Gosh, he said…
-"I will!"

1166
00:48:49,793 --> 00:48:53,597
But Chef Sung-jun declined it.

1167
00:48:53,664 --> 00:48:55,666
I'll use the one-minute stop.

1168
00:48:55,732 --> 00:48:57,534
-He'll use that.
-My gosh.

1169
00:48:57,601 --> 00:49:00,070
One-minute salsa dance was harder.

1170
00:49:00,137 --> 00:49:03,407
Chef Sam if you end up winning,

1171
00:49:03,473 --> 00:49:06,543
you can win against all chefs
of <i>Culinary Class Wars</i> with one try.

1172
00:49:06,610 --> 00:49:08,412
Yes, you're right.

1173
00:49:08,478 --> 00:49:10,480
-Yes.
-You can take all his victories.

1174
00:49:10,547 --> 00:49:12,182
You would've won against all 100.

1175
00:49:12,249 --> 00:49:15,886
But the important thing is this.
Joong-ki is the judge.

1176
00:49:15,953 --> 00:49:19,489
I watched him eat
the three different dishes right now

1177
00:49:19,556 --> 00:49:21,625
and finished analyzing his palate.

1178
00:49:23,126 --> 00:49:24,795
-I see.
-He analyzed him?

1179
00:49:24,861 --> 00:49:26,330
He already finished analyzing.

1180
00:49:26,396 --> 00:49:29,066
-Can we try the leftovers?
-Sure.

1181
00:49:29,900 --> 00:49:32,302
-Do you prefer salty food?
-Me?

1182
00:49:32,369 --> 00:49:34,805
How salty do you take Italian food?

1183
00:49:34,871 --> 00:49:37,207
I just dip it when it tastes a bit bland.

1184
00:49:37,274 --> 00:49:39,443
PALATE ANALYSIS COMPLETED

1185
00:49:39,509 --> 00:49:42,646
He asked you
while we weren't even watching.

1186
00:49:42,713 --> 00:49:44,681
Sam, did you ask?

1187
00:49:44,748 --> 00:49:45,882
I didn't.

1188
00:49:45,949 --> 00:49:47,951
You could've done that.

1189
00:49:48,018 --> 00:49:50,287
-Analyze him!
-What will you do with your mouth?

1190
00:49:50,354 --> 00:49:54,658
Chef Sung-jun is moving swiftly
in this situation.

1191
00:49:55,258 --> 00:49:56,326
CHEF SUNG-JUN'S INGREDIENTS:
PARMIGIANO,

1192
00:49:56,393 --> 00:49:57,527
PUFF PASTRY, RASPBERRY CHOCOLATE,
BECHAMEL

1193
00:49:57,594 --> 00:49:58,695
SPINACH, BUCKWHEAT ORZO,
OLIVE OIL, SALSA,

1194
00:49:58,762 --> 00:49:59,863
CHICKEN STOCK, SALAMI,
GUANCIALE, AND MORE

1195
00:49:59,930 --> 00:50:01,465
I prepared a dish called

1196
00:50:01,531 --> 00:50:03,100
Matfia Risotto.

1197
00:50:03,166 --> 00:50:05,135
-Matfia Risotto.
-Matfia Risotto.

1198
00:50:05,202 --> 00:50:07,337
Can you make risotto in 15 minutes?

1199
00:50:07,404 --> 00:50:10,807
It's impossible to do in 15 minutes,

1200
00:50:10,874 --> 00:50:12,943
if I may say that as an expert.

1201
00:50:13,010 --> 00:50:16,747
<i>But you made 100 servings in 20 minutes.</i>

1202
00:50:16,813 --> 00:50:20,851
The time it takes to make risotto
is the same for 100 servings or 1.

1203
00:50:20,917 --> 00:50:23,153
-We decided on the perfect limit.
-Yes.

1204
00:50:23,220 --> 00:50:24,921
-He needs more time.
-The five minutes.

1205
00:50:24,988 --> 00:50:28,058
But I saw this rice-shaped pasta

1206
00:50:28,125 --> 00:50:30,894
called orzo in his fridge.

1207
00:50:30,961 --> 00:50:34,197
I'll make a dish
that's between risotto and pasta.

1208
00:50:34,264 --> 00:50:38,001
-You said it was baby food, right?
-You're right.

1209
00:50:38,068 --> 00:50:41,004
Chef Sung-jun brought his own pan.

1210
00:50:41,071 --> 00:50:42,606
Yes, it's my favorite frying pan.

1211
00:50:42,672 --> 00:50:43,774
HE BROUGHT HIS OWN PAN

1212
00:50:43,840 --> 00:50:46,309
He was the first chef
to bring his own pan.

1213
00:50:46,376 --> 00:50:48,078
I used this to win <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>.

1214
00:50:48,145 --> 00:50:49,980
To win <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>?

1215
00:50:50,047 --> 00:50:52,015
-Gosh.
-It has that luck.

1216
00:50:52,082 --> 00:50:53,650
That was why you brought it.

1217
00:50:53,717 --> 00:50:54,918
CHEF SAM KIM'S INGREDIENTS:
PARMIGIANO,

1218
00:50:54,985 --> 00:50:55,986
PORCINI, CANNED TUNA, STRIP LOIN

1219
00:50:56,053 --> 00:50:58,188
GUANCIALE, CABBAGE, LENTIL,
CHICKEN STOCK, OLIVE OIL, RISOTTO RICE

1220
00:50:58,255 --> 00:50:59,990
I prepared a dish called

1221
00:51:00,057 --> 00:51:01,992
Vinsamzo Risotto.

1222
00:51:02,059 --> 00:51:04,027
-What?
-Vinsamzo?

1223
00:51:04,094 --> 00:51:06,463
-Vinsamzo? You're making risotto too?
-They both are.

1224
00:51:06,530 --> 00:51:07,798
Vinsamzo Risotto.

1225
00:51:07,864 --> 00:51:11,668
Actually. you all think it's impossible
to make risotto in 15 minutes,

1226
00:51:11,735 --> 00:51:15,005
but I'll cook the risotto
in just 15 minutes.

1227
00:51:15,072 --> 00:51:17,007
You'll use real rice?

1228
00:51:17,074 --> 00:51:18,475
Yes, from the start to finish.

1229
00:51:18,542 --> 00:51:19,609
He's using actual rice.

1230
00:51:19,676 --> 00:51:22,179
-Everyone said it was impossible.
-We did.

1231
00:51:22,245 --> 00:51:23,947
-It's impossible.
-But he says he can.

1232
00:51:24,014 --> 00:51:25,782
But I thought I could

1233
00:51:25,849 --> 00:51:29,352
get it to around <i>al dente</i>.

1234
00:51:29,419 --> 00:51:31,455
-You can get it to <i>al dente</i>?
-It'd be amazing if you did.

1235
00:51:31,521 --> 00:51:35,459
It may not go to <i>al dente</i>,
and you may end up serving raw rice.

1236
00:51:35,525 --> 00:51:38,161
I believe it's possible.

1237
00:51:38,228 --> 00:51:39,930
If he says it is, then it is.

1238
00:51:39,996 --> 00:51:42,199
While I wait for that to cook,

1239
00:51:42,265 --> 00:51:44,101
you said you also liked tuna.

1240
00:51:44,167 --> 00:51:47,404
There's a traditional dish from Piedmont
called <i>Vitello tonnato</i>.

1241
00:51:47,471 --> 00:51:49,005
There's this dish you eat

1242
00:51:49,072 --> 00:51:51,641
-with tuna sauce on top of veal.
-That's so cool.

1243
00:51:51,708 --> 00:51:53,310
And also,

1244
00:51:53,376 --> 00:51:54,945
while I wait for that…

1245
00:51:55,011 --> 00:51:56,012
Again?

1246
00:51:56,079 --> 00:51:59,649
I saw the lentils and guanciale,
a type of Italian ham.

1247
00:51:59,716 --> 00:52:03,086
If you eat those together
in this soup-like dish, it'll be great.

1248
00:52:03,153 --> 00:52:05,388
-Gosh.
-In 15 minutes?

1249
00:52:05,455 --> 00:52:08,325
-I want to make three dishes.
-Three?

1250
00:52:08,391 --> 00:52:09,626
Here's my take.

1251
00:52:09,693 --> 00:52:11,294
You're making three dishes

1252
00:52:11,361 --> 00:52:14,197
in case your risotto completely fails.

1253
00:52:14,264 --> 00:52:17,667
I think he's preparing plan B and plan C.

1254
00:52:17,734 --> 00:52:19,736
But you called it risotto,

1255
00:52:19,803 --> 00:52:21,972
-so you have to have that.
-That's right.

1256
00:52:22,038 --> 00:52:24,708
Let us begin the round

1257
00:52:24,774 --> 00:52:28,311
for the order "It's me, olive oil."

1258
00:52:28,812 --> 00:52:29,813
I'm nervous.

1259
00:52:29,880 --> 00:52:31,748
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i> is my turf!

1260
00:52:31,815 --> 00:52:35,752
The original Italian chef is here
with his pride to teach him a lesson.

1261
00:52:35,819 --> 00:52:37,821
Chef Sam Kim is up.

1262
00:52:37,888 --> 00:52:40,056
He's the first place
of <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>,

1263
00:52:40,123 --> 00:52:42,659
and he's here to take over
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i>, too.

1264
00:52:42,726 --> 00:52:46,696
Napoli Matfia, Chef Kwon Sung-jun is
up against Chef Sam.

1265
00:52:46,763 --> 00:52:48,765
The rival match between Italian chefs.

1266
00:52:48,832 --> 00:52:50,667
Who'll be the winner?

1267
00:52:50,734 --> 00:52:54,004
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1268
00:52:55,505 --> 00:52:57,207
This is a huge match.

1269
00:52:57,274 --> 00:53:00,076
Who will become the best Italian chef?

1270
00:53:00,143 --> 00:53:01,745
They need all the time for the risotto,

1271
00:53:01,811 --> 00:53:03,780
-so they should start there.
-You're right.

1272
00:53:03,847 --> 00:53:07,384
-The rice first.
-Sam needs to start with the risotto.

1273
00:53:07,450 --> 00:53:08,451
You're right.

1274
00:53:08,518 --> 00:53:11,621
They both don't have enough time.

1275
00:53:11,688 --> 00:53:13,323
THIS IS THE SOUND
OF PORCINI GETTING CHOPPED

1276
00:53:13,390 --> 00:53:14,791
-What's that? Mushrooms?
-Mushrooms.

1277
00:53:14,858 --> 00:53:16,693
-Porcini.
-Right, porcini.

1278
00:53:16,760 --> 00:53:18,161
PORCINI: TEXTURE LIKE MEAT,
SMELLS LIKE THE FOREST

1279
00:53:18,228 --> 00:53:20,130
He chopped up porcini.

1280
00:53:20,197 --> 00:53:21,565
NEXT, RISOTTO RICE!

1281
00:53:21,631 --> 00:53:23,300
The risotto rice goes in.

1282
00:53:23,366 --> 00:53:26,169
Sam Kim wants to make risotto
with rice from scratch.

1283
00:53:26,236 --> 00:53:28,538
I don't think it'll cool thoroughly.

1284
00:53:30,507 --> 00:53:32,142
What's Chef Sung-jun chopping?

1285
00:53:32,209 --> 00:53:33,310
Guanciale.

1286
00:53:33,376 --> 00:53:36,546
He's using
all kinds of Italian ingredients.

1287
00:53:36,613 --> 00:53:38,315
GUANCIALE: SALTED PORK CHEEKS

1288
00:53:38,882 --> 00:53:41,718
Chef Sung-jun is using his own pan.

1289
00:53:41,785 --> 00:53:43,954
-It's so shiny.
-It is.

1290
00:53:44,020 --> 00:53:46,890
It feels like it has its own lights.

1291
00:53:46,957 --> 00:53:49,526
CHEF SAM ALSO ADDS
OLIVE OIL IN THE POT

1292
00:53:49,593 --> 00:53:50,961
It's been a minute.

1293
00:53:51,027 --> 00:53:52,862
Really? Time flies.

1294
00:53:52,929 --> 00:53:55,899
He's also chopping guanciale.

1295
00:53:55,966 --> 00:53:58,735
Hurry up.
It's been a minute, but the rice…

1296
00:53:58,802 --> 00:54:00,203
Yes.

1297
00:54:00,270 --> 00:54:02,172
He's frying the rice.

1298
00:54:04,274 --> 00:54:08,411
Risotto is all about what you do
before you throw in the broth.

1299
00:54:08,478 --> 00:54:11,514
When there's just oil without broth,
the rice can burn.

1300
00:54:11,581 --> 00:54:14,384
You can turn down the heat
once you add the broth, but…

1301
00:54:14,451 --> 00:54:16,086
This is a critical moment.

1302
00:54:16,152 --> 00:54:17,854
Sam has trouble peeling the chicken stock.

1303
00:54:17,921 --> 00:54:20,156
-I want him to stop.
-Stop!

1304
00:54:20,223 --> 00:54:22,525
-Stop!
-Stop!

1305
00:54:22,592 --> 00:54:24,628
-I want him to stop.
-Stop!

1306
00:54:24,694 --> 00:54:27,998
-Right now? Wait!
-My gosh.

1307
00:54:30,066 --> 00:54:31,568
Geez!

1308
00:54:31,635 --> 00:54:32,902
Oh, my gosh.

1309
00:54:32,969 --> 00:54:34,537
The fire. The risotto.

1310
00:54:34,604 --> 00:54:35,639
Take it off.

1311
00:54:35,705 --> 00:54:37,841
Take it off the heat for now.

1312
00:54:37,907 --> 00:54:38,908
You can't touch it.

1313
00:54:38,975 --> 00:54:41,544
My gosh. As soon as you begin?

1314
00:54:41,611 --> 00:54:44,080
He stops him too early in the battle.

1315
00:54:44,147 --> 00:54:45,849
I've known Sam for a long time,

1316
00:54:45,915 --> 00:54:49,519
and I've never seen him make
such awful face before.

1317
00:54:49,586 --> 00:54:51,588
It seemed like he was mad.

1318
00:54:52,856 --> 00:54:54,457
The timing was very important just now.

1319
00:54:54,524 --> 00:54:57,494
His hands look so restless.

1320
00:54:57,560 --> 00:54:59,896
Sam turns his hand into a fist.

1321
00:54:59,963 --> 00:55:02,032
Thirty seconds.

1322
00:55:02,098 --> 00:55:04,367
-Chef Sung-jun isn't joking around.
-He's scary.

1323
00:55:04,434 --> 00:55:06,636
Is this what <i>Culinary Class Wars</i> is like?
It's so scary!

1324
00:55:06,703 --> 00:55:08,705
Gosh, he had just begun.

1325
00:55:08,772 --> 00:55:10,340
It was unexpected.

1326
00:55:10,407 --> 00:55:12,175
-He used it too early.
-It was unexpected.

1327
00:55:12,242 --> 00:55:14,544
When he said this timing was important.

1328
00:55:14,611 --> 00:55:15,812
Ten seconds.

1329
00:55:15,879 --> 00:55:18,548
I shouldn't have said that.
I said that for nothing.

1330
00:55:18,615 --> 00:55:19,916
He used it too early on.

1331
00:55:19,983 --> 00:55:22,285
Four. Three.

1332
00:55:22,352 --> 00:55:24,387
-Two. One.
-Two. One.

1333
00:55:24,454 --> 00:55:26,923
-You're free!
-You're free to start.

1334
00:55:26,990 --> 00:55:27,991
You can go.

1335
00:55:28,058 --> 00:55:30,360
That took up too much time.

1336
00:55:30,427 --> 00:55:32,962
-Sam looked flustered.
-Look at the time.

1337
00:55:33,029 --> 00:55:35,398
Sam said in some cooking show

1338
00:55:35,465 --> 00:55:37,600
that you should never use
too much water for risotto.

1339
00:55:37,667 --> 00:55:42,339
But he put in a lot of broth
and turn the heat on to cook faster.

1340
00:55:42,405 --> 00:55:43,606
Did the cooking method change?

1341
00:55:43,673 --> 00:55:45,141
It's a little different.

1342
00:55:45,208 --> 00:55:48,111
-But I believe he'll find his taste.
-Yes.

1343
00:55:48,178 --> 00:55:49,179
Gosh.

1344
00:55:49,245 --> 00:55:51,614
-Chef Sam was stabbed in the back.
-He was.

1345
00:55:51,681 --> 00:55:54,317
If you think about it,
Chef Hyun-suk stabbed him in the back.

1346
00:55:54,384 --> 00:55:56,052
He told him when to use it.

1347
00:55:56,119 --> 00:55:58,822
I didn't tell him to use it.
I just said that timing was important.

1348
00:55:58,888 --> 00:56:00,390
It's the same thing!

1349
00:56:00,457 --> 00:56:01,691
I'M SORRY, SAM

1350
00:56:01,758 --> 00:56:05,395
-Will Sam overcome this difficulty?
-Will he push through?

1351
00:56:06,496 --> 00:56:08,164
4. STIR-FRY LENTILS, CABBAGE,
AND GARLIC IN THE GUANCIALE PAN

1352
00:56:08,231 --> 00:56:09,833
-What's that? Cabbage?
-Yes, cabbage.

1353
00:56:09,899 --> 00:56:11,368
He's stir-frying cabbage?

1354
00:56:12,369 --> 00:56:13,770
You have ten minutes!

1355
00:56:13,837 --> 00:56:15,572
You're under ten minutes now.

1356
00:56:15,638 --> 00:56:17,374
SALSA SAUCE

1357
00:56:18,975 --> 00:56:20,577
-What's that?
-What is that?

1358
00:56:20,643 --> 00:56:22,345
Milk?

1359
00:56:23,213 --> 00:56:25,348
My wife used that to make lasagna.

1360
00:56:25,415 --> 00:56:26,449
What's that?

1361
00:56:26,516 --> 00:56:27,517
Bechamel.

1362
00:56:27,584 --> 00:56:30,153
-Bechamel?
-He had bechamel?

1363
00:56:30,220 --> 00:56:31,621
They sell that as a product?

1364
00:56:31,688 --> 00:56:33,056
-Yes.
-Actually,

1365
00:56:33,123 --> 00:56:35,692
you mix flour with butter,
then add milk to make that sauce.

1366
00:56:35,759 --> 00:56:38,895
It's one of the basic white sauces.

1367
00:56:38,962 --> 00:56:42,098
My wife always brought that here
from Italy to make lasagna

1368
00:56:42,165 --> 00:56:45,101
because it was hard to find that here.

1369
00:56:45,835 --> 00:56:46,970
Are you adding ketchup?

1370
00:56:47,537 --> 00:56:49,672
I didn't see any tomato puree.

1371
00:56:49,739 --> 00:56:51,174
It's replacing tomato.

1372
00:56:54,210 --> 00:56:55,412
There was actual tomato too.

1373
00:56:55,478 --> 00:56:58,181
-There was tomato, but he used ketchup.
-He did.

1374
00:56:58,248 --> 00:57:00,750
Korean tomatoes taste too watery,

1375
00:57:00,817 --> 00:57:03,920
so I need the puree.
These will only help a little.

1376
00:57:03,987 --> 00:57:07,190
-Doesn't it look a bit salty? It does.
-It does.

1377
00:57:07,257 --> 00:57:08,925
I didn't put any salt in it.

1378
00:57:08,992 --> 00:57:10,160
THIS IS SALT

1379
00:57:10,226 --> 00:57:11,761
You can still explain what you're doing.

1380
00:57:11,828 --> 00:57:13,930
-Yes, he's so relaxed.
-He is.

1381
00:57:13,997 --> 00:57:16,499
-I thought he'd be flustered, but no.
-No.

1382
00:57:16,566 --> 00:57:17,901
-Chef Kang-rok.
-Yes?

1383
00:57:17,967 --> 00:57:20,370
What do you think
about Chef Sung-jun's performance?

1384
00:57:20,437 --> 00:57:21,905
Well, I'm jealous.

1385
00:57:24,541 --> 00:57:26,443
-Is he doing well?
-Yes.

1386
00:57:26,509 --> 00:57:27,544
Why are you jealous?

1387
00:57:27,610 --> 00:57:29,245
I envy his confidence.

1388
00:57:29,312 --> 00:57:31,114
He envies that confidence.

1389
00:57:31,181 --> 00:57:34,184
You'll also become as confident as him
once you're familiar with the show.

1390
00:57:34,250 --> 00:57:35,952
You'll get used to it soon.

1391
00:57:36,019 --> 00:57:37,587
Is he making tuile with cheese?

1392
00:57:37,654 --> 00:57:39,722
5. TOAST PARMIGIANO AND PECORINO
OVER A DRY PAN TO MAKE TUILE

1393
00:57:40,523 --> 00:57:41,791
THE BIGGEST SECRET,
KOREAN STRIP LOIN

1394
00:57:41,858 --> 00:57:44,561
How will you use the meat, Chef Sam?

1395
00:57:44,627 --> 00:57:47,964
-It's softening it.
-I'll flatten it and parboil it.

1396
00:57:48,031 --> 00:57:49,732
Is that for the risotto?

1397
00:57:49,799 --> 00:57:52,035
No, I'll serve it with tuna sauce.

1398
00:57:52,101 --> 00:57:53,903
The meat and tuna thing?

1399
00:57:53,970 --> 00:57:56,206
5. FLATTEN STRIP LOIN
WITH A MEAT POUNDER

1400
00:57:56,272 --> 00:57:58,208
He just flattened the meat completely.

1401
00:57:58,274 --> 00:57:59,976
CANNED TUNA

1402
00:58:00,043 --> 00:58:01,511
VINEGAR, SALT

1403
00:58:01,578 --> 00:58:03,379
WHAT'S HE PICKING UP?

1404
00:58:03,446 --> 00:58:04,814
BOILED EGG

1405
00:58:04,881 --> 00:58:06,149
The egg must be hard to peel.

1406
00:58:06,216 --> 00:58:08,751
Sam's hands are trembling.

1407
00:58:08,818 --> 00:58:11,221
It's been five years… No, the egg!

1408
00:58:11,287 --> 00:58:14,023
-He's using that? Oh, he's blending it.
-He must be.

1409
00:58:14,090 --> 00:58:15,558
6. BLEND CANNED TUNA,
VINEGAR, SALT, EGG,

1410
00:58:15,625 --> 00:58:16,826
AND OLIVE OIL TO MAKE TUNA SAUCE

1411
00:58:16,893 --> 00:58:20,730
Sam just blended tuna and boiled egg.

1412
00:58:20,797 --> 00:58:22,599
He just blended it in a blender.

1413
00:58:23,366 --> 00:58:25,001
HOW WILL HE FIGHT AGAINST THE TUNA?

1414
00:58:25,068 --> 00:58:27,737
He's blending something too. What is it?

1415
00:58:27,804 --> 00:58:29,973
-Pecans.
-Pecans?

1416
00:58:30,039 --> 00:58:32,342
-What do pecans taste like?
-They're like walnuts.

1417
00:58:32,408 --> 00:58:35,712
Walnuts are a little round,
but they're a bit more oval-shaped.

1418
00:58:35,778 --> 00:58:39,148
-It's a bit crunchier.
-Yes, it is crunchier.

1419
00:58:40,149 --> 00:58:41,150
SNIFFING

1420
00:58:41,751 --> 00:58:44,120
What did you just throw in?

1421
00:58:44,187 --> 00:58:46,155
-Spinach.
-Spinach.

1422
00:58:46,222 --> 00:58:48,525
-Gosh.
-He had spinach?

1423
00:58:48,591 --> 00:58:50,126
It must be frozen spinach.

1424
00:58:50,193 --> 00:58:52,529
He's putting in a lot of work
into the risotto sauce.

1425
00:58:52,595 --> 00:58:55,632
Chef Sung-jun continuously controls
the amount of water.

1426
00:58:55,698 --> 00:58:57,100
The ingredients are

1427
00:58:57,166 --> 00:58:59,669
all from Italy,

1428
00:58:59,736 --> 00:59:02,572
so it's hard to tell.

1429
00:59:02,639 --> 00:59:04,941
7. ADD GREASE FROM GUANCIALE
TO RISOTTO FOR MORE FLAVOR

1430
00:59:07,377 --> 00:59:09,445
There's his plan B.

1431
00:59:09,512 --> 00:59:10,914
He's parboiling it briefly.

1432
00:59:10,980 --> 00:59:12,916
-He's parboiling the beef.
-He is.

1433
00:59:12,982 --> 00:59:15,151
Yes, he parboiled it.

1434
00:59:16,486 --> 00:59:19,722
Can you just leave the risotto there
without stirring it?

1435
00:59:19,789 --> 00:59:21,724
No, I should do that.

1436
00:59:21,791 --> 00:59:22,992
Yes, he's shaking it.

1437
00:59:23,560 --> 00:59:26,629
Yes, the risotto.
It boiled down quite a bit.

1438
00:59:26,696 --> 00:59:28,264
He's adding more broth.

1439
00:59:30,166 --> 00:59:31,768
Will he finish making that?

1440
00:59:31,834 --> 00:59:34,037
He has to keep paying attention to that.

1441
00:59:34,103 --> 00:59:37,206
-It'll burn if he looks away.
-It'll smell burnt.

1442
00:59:38,141 --> 00:59:39,409
Where are the lentils?

1443
00:59:39,475 --> 00:59:41,477
It's in there with the cabbage.

1444
00:59:41,544 --> 00:59:43,146
-The lentils are with the cabbage?
-Yes.

1445
00:59:44,914 --> 00:59:48,952
9. ADD TOMATO TO THE LENTIL SOUP
AND BRING TO A BOIL

1446
00:59:49,719 --> 00:59:51,287
The tension is high.

1447
00:59:51,354 --> 00:59:53,456
What's important is olive oil.

1448
00:59:53,957 --> 00:59:55,825
It smells so good.

1449
00:59:56,392 --> 00:59:57,860
Whose dish smells like this?

1450
00:59:57,927 --> 00:59:59,796
Which side is it coming from?

1451
00:59:59,862 --> 01:00:01,297
-It smells nutty.
-Then…

1452
01:00:01,364 --> 01:00:03,900
Isn't it because he ground up pecans?

1453
01:00:03,967 --> 01:00:06,469
-Yes, the risotto.
-I think it's this side.

1454
01:00:06,536 --> 01:00:08,171
Gosh, it smells great.

1455
01:00:08,237 --> 01:00:09,872
IT ALREADY SMELLS LIKE ITALY

1456
01:00:09,939 --> 01:00:12,475
Joong-ki, which smell do you prefer?

1457
01:00:12,542 --> 01:00:14,644
-They're mixed up.
-Mixed up?

1458
01:00:14,711 --> 01:00:17,046
-Everything smells good.
-So far, everything smells good.

1459
01:00:17,113 --> 01:00:18,247
They have five minutes.

1460
01:00:18,314 --> 01:00:19,349
-Five minutes!
-Five minutes left.

1461
01:00:19,415 --> 01:00:20,950
We have five minutes left.

1462
01:00:21,017 --> 01:00:23,753
-Jung-hwan is going out to the field.
-Yes!

1463
01:00:23,820 --> 01:00:25,088
CAN THEY FINISH THE RISOTTO
IN 5 MINUTES?

1464
01:00:25,154 --> 01:00:27,423
A battle between two Italian dishes.

1465
01:00:28,257 --> 01:00:29,425
RASPBERRY CHOCOLATE

1466
01:00:29,492 --> 01:00:30,994
He took something out.

1467
01:00:31,060 --> 01:00:34,397
It was in the fridge before.
What's Chef Sung-jun using?

1468
01:00:34,464 --> 01:00:36,733
-What's that?
-Pastry. Puff pastry.

1469
01:00:36,799 --> 01:00:38,368
Oh, puff pastry.

1470
01:00:38,434 --> 01:00:42,271
It's what you use to make croissants.

1471
01:00:42,338 --> 01:00:45,375
Unlike in Korea,
they sell that dough like that.

1472
01:00:45,441 --> 01:00:47,744
They sell that dough? I see salami too.

1473
01:00:47,810 --> 01:00:49,479
Why did you get the puff pastry?

1474
01:00:49,545 --> 01:00:51,514
It won't be easy to cook in four minutes.

1475
01:00:51,581 --> 01:00:53,016
Right? What will he do with it?

1476
01:00:53,082 --> 01:00:54,651
Is this parched rice?

1477
01:00:55,218 --> 01:00:57,053
-Something like that.
-I see.

1478
01:00:57,120 --> 01:00:59,055
-You already threw in orzo.
-Yes.

1479
01:01:00,056 --> 01:01:01,057
-Jung-hwan!
-Yes?

1480
01:01:01,124 --> 01:01:03,660
We have four minutes and two seconds.
Can you try that?

1481
01:01:03,726 --> 01:01:05,862
-It's not cooked yet.
-Sure! It's not cooked yet.

1482
01:01:05,928 --> 01:01:08,765
It's okay!
You need to tell us at four minutes.

1483
01:01:08,831 --> 01:01:10,099
-All right.
-"It's okay"?

1484
01:01:10,166 --> 01:01:13,736
-Gosh, this is…
-How is it at four minutes?

1485
01:01:13,803 --> 01:01:15,271
This is Chef Sung-jun's dish.

1486
01:01:15,338 --> 01:01:16,572
CAUTIOUS

1487
01:01:16,639 --> 01:01:18,941
What's it like right now?

1488
01:01:20,276 --> 01:01:23,179
-I'm about to lose my teeth.
-Oh, no.

1489
01:01:23,246 --> 01:01:25,515
-It must be that hard.
-I'm about to lose my teeth.

1490
01:01:25,581 --> 01:01:28,885
-Oh, no. Is it hard?
-It's still hard.

1491
01:01:29,519 --> 01:01:31,187
It must be really hard.

1492
01:01:31,254 --> 01:01:33,489
That needs to get cooked even more.

1493
01:01:33,556 --> 01:01:35,024
-You tasted it, right?
-Yes.

1494
01:01:35,091 --> 01:01:37,493
-You still have some time.
-Gosh, right now…

1495
01:01:37,560 --> 01:01:38,561
This is bad.

1496
01:01:38,628 --> 01:01:40,763
-"This is bad"?
-It's bad?

1497
01:01:40,830 --> 01:01:42,565
"This is bad." Chef Sung-jun is flustered.

1498
01:01:42,632 --> 01:01:44,701
He won the first place
of <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>.

1499
01:01:44,767 --> 01:01:45,935
What did he say about winning?

1500
01:01:46,002 --> 01:01:47,270
He said it was a given.

1501
01:01:47,336 --> 01:01:48,471
But right now, things look bad.

1502
01:01:48,538 --> 01:01:50,273
You'd be humiliated
if you serve raw pasta!

1503
01:01:50,339 --> 01:01:52,208
I still have a piece stuck in my teeth.

1504
01:01:52,842 --> 01:01:53,843
I have a piece in here.

1505
01:01:53,910 --> 01:01:55,278
WILL IT BE DONE
IN 3 MINUTES AND 30 SECONDS?

1506
01:01:55,344 --> 01:01:57,380
-Gosh, this is bad.
-What about this side?

1507
01:01:57,447 --> 01:01:58,715
What now?

1508
01:01:58,781 --> 01:02:01,751
10. ADD PORCINI WATER INTO RISOTTO

1509
01:02:01,818 --> 01:02:03,586
Now, Sam's dish.

1510
01:02:03,653 --> 01:02:07,190
-He's using real rice.
-It still looks raw to my eyes.

1511
01:02:09,525 --> 01:02:10,793
SAM KIM'S PLAN B IS FINISHED

1512
01:02:10,860 --> 01:02:12,395
But the risotto is his main dish.

1513
01:02:12,962 --> 01:02:15,231
Let me tell you once again
that the risotto is the main dish.

1514
01:02:15,298 --> 01:02:17,366
What's he using the puff pastry for?

1515
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:20,203
<i>Contiamo tre minuti!</i> Three minutes left.

1516
01:02:21,204 --> 01:02:22,438
HE TRIES TO CUT IT OUT

1517
01:02:22,505 --> 01:02:23,906
-What?
-Is it frozen?

1518
01:02:23,973 --> 01:02:26,175
-Darn it, it's stuck!
-The risotto.

1519
01:02:26,242 --> 01:02:28,244
-He said, "Darn it."
-"Darn it."

1520
01:02:28,311 --> 01:02:31,047
Wait, look! "Darn it, it's stuck!"

1521
01:02:31,114 --> 01:02:33,616
Chef Sung-jun begins to let out
some curses.

1522
01:02:33,683 --> 01:02:36,953
He has less than three minutes,
but the puff pastry is still uncooked.

1523
01:02:37,019 --> 01:02:39,322
I don't know if he can cook that
in three minutes?

1524
01:02:39,388 --> 01:02:40,990
It's impossible to cook with that time.

1525
01:02:41,057 --> 01:02:42,992
How is he going to handle that?

1526
01:02:43,059 --> 01:02:44,794
I think he's playing with it.

1527
01:02:44,861 --> 01:02:46,929
-Frying?
-Will he deep-fry it?

1528
01:02:46,996 --> 01:02:50,199
He's frying it.
That way, he can cook it quickly.

1529
01:02:50,266 --> 01:02:53,202
-Let me try this risotto.
-Sam's dish.

1530
01:02:53,269 --> 01:02:55,104
Sam's risotto.

1531
01:02:56,205 --> 01:02:57,340
How is it?

1532
01:02:57,406 --> 01:02:58,775
HE BEGAN WITH RAW RICE

1533
01:02:58,841 --> 01:03:00,777
This guy is in trouble too!

1534
01:03:01,310 --> 01:03:03,546
This guy is in trouble too!

1535
01:03:03,613 --> 01:03:05,114
Oh, I can't watch this.

1536
01:03:05,181 --> 01:03:07,016
Gosh, I can't watch.

1537
01:03:07,083 --> 01:03:09,352
-There's just not enough time.
-Two minutes and twenty seconds.

1538
01:03:09,418 --> 01:03:10,620
-Gosh.
-Is it uncooked?

1539
01:03:10,686 --> 01:03:12,889
-It's not.
-It's not cooked?

1540
01:03:12,955 --> 01:03:14,724
-He's running out of time.
-It needs to be cooked more.

1541
01:03:14,791 --> 01:03:17,193
-<i>Mantecare!</i>
-Whoa, he's doing this.

1542
01:03:17,260 --> 01:03:19,095
Shouldn't you turn the heat up?

1543
01:03:20,029 --> 01:03:22,565
I tasted both dishes,

1544
01:03:22,632 --> 01:03:24,300
and they both smell like Italy.

1545
01:03:24,367 --> 01:03:26,369
-Do they?
-Yes, they taste heavenly.

1546
01:03:26,435 --> 01:03:29,872
-But both the rice and orzo aren't cooked.
-I see.

1547
01:03:29,939 --> 01:03:31,040
I don't know how that'll go.

1548
01:03:31,107 --> 01:03:35,244
The risotto looks too wet
with only 1 minute and 50 seconds left.

1549
01:03:35,311 --> 01:03:38,381
-Only one minute or so.
-The fry may burn!

1550
01:03:38,447 --> 01:03:40,917
Is that okay, Chef Sung-jun?

1551
01:03:40,983 --> 01:03:43,786
-It's about to burn.
-It got cooked.

1552
01:03:43,853 --> 01:03:46,455
The color looks completely different.

1553
01:03:46,522 --> 01:03:48,624
This one looks fully cooked.

1554
01:03:49,192 --> 01:03:51,961
This means both of them
may not end up finishing the dishes.

1555
01:03:52,028 --> 01:03:54,363
Chef Sam began to serve the dishes.
What's this?

1556
01:03:54,430 --> 01:03:56,098
-Lentils.
-Lentils.

1557
01:03:56,165 --> 01:03:57,433
11. GRATE PARMIGIANO ON THE TOP

1558
01:03:57,500 --> 01:03:59,235
He's putting cheese over the lentils.

1559
01:03:59,302 --> 01:04:01,537
You have a minute left.

1560
01:04:01,604 --> 01:04:02,905
One minute. <i>Un minuto!</i>

1561
01:04:02,972 --> 01:04:04,307
-One minute.
-One minute.

1562
01:04:04,373 --> 01:04:05,641
The clock ticks down.

1563
01:04:05,708 --> 01:04:08,177
You have one minute.
The timer now turned red.

1564
01:04:08,244 --> 01:04:12,281
But his risotto looks more like rice soup.

1565
01:04:12,348 --> 01:04:15,251
Chefs, will the risotto be ready?

1566
01:04:15,318 --> 01:04:16,319
HEAT OFF

1567
01:04:16,385 --> 01:04:18,187
Will the risotto be ready?

1568
01:04:18,254 --> 01:04:20,923
Joong-ki came with high expectations.

1569
01:04:20,990 --> 01:04:23,860
The Italian dishes are about to be ruined.

1570
01:04:23,926 --> 01:04:25,027
I need cheese too.

1571
01:04:25,094 --> 01:04:27,430
-He needs cheese.
-The cheese.

1572
01:04:27,496 --> 01:04:29,832
He could've picked it up.
Why did he demand it?

1573
01:04:29,899 --> 01:04:31,400
Chef Sam is out of time too.

1574
01:04:31,467 --> 01:04:33,102
But he's so nice and gave it to him.

1575
01:04:33,169 --> 01:04:34,170
-Forty seconds.
-Forty seconds.

1576
01:04:34,237 --> 01:04:35,705
Forty seconds.

1577
01:04:35,771 --> 01:04:36,973
Let me ask you one last time.

1578
01:04:37,039 --> 01:04:39,642
Will the risotto be ready?

1579
01:04:41,010 --> 01:04:42,345
Will the risotto be ready?

1580
01:04:42,411 --> 01:04:44,313
-I think it's out!
-Chef Sam's risotto!

1581
01:04:44,380 --> 01:04:45,381
Chef Sam is serving!

1582
01:04:45,948 --> 01:04:47,116
-Chef Sam!
-He's serving!

1583
01:04:47,183 --> 01:04:50,119
-Twenty-six seconds.
-Twenty-five seconds!

1584
01:04:50,186 --> 01:04:53,456
The risotto can get colder,
so it'll be advantageous to finish first.

1585
01:04:53,522 --> 01:04:55,057
-Yes.
-Who'll finish first?

1586
01:04:55,124 --> 01:04:57,226
Chef Sam is done!

1587
01:04:57,293 --> 01:04:58,427
Chef Sam is finished!

1588
01:04:58,494 --> 01:05:00,830
-Chef Sam is done!
-Chef Sam is finished!

1589
01:05:01,697 --> 01:05:04,200
Now, the other Show-off Chef.

1590
01:05:04,267 --> 01:05:05,801
HE CONTINUES TO GRATE CHEESE
AT 15 SECONDS

1591
01:05:05,868 --> 01:05:07,703
He's adding a lot of cheese.
That's a good idea.

1592
01:05:07,770 --> 01:05:09,272
-Ten.
-Show-off Chef.

1593
01:05:09,338 --> 01:05:10,406
-Nine.
-Nine.

1594
01:05:10,473 --> 01:05:12,141
Eight. Seven.

1595
01:05:12,875 --> 01:05:16,946
THE FINISHING TOUCH
FOR THE RISOTTO

1596
01:05:17,914 --> 01:05:20,816
IT'S AMAZING TO WATCH IN REAL LIFE

1597
01:05:20,883 --> 01:05:22,184
Eight.

1598
01:05:22,251 --> 01:05:23,452
Seven.

1599
01:05:23,519 --> 01:05:24,520
Six.

1600
01:05:24,587 --> 01:05:25,588
-Five.
-Five.

1601
01:05:26,322 --> 01:05:28,024
-What was that?
-Three.

1602
01:05:28,090 --> 01:05:29,225
-What happened?
-Two.

1603
01:05:29,292 --> 01:05:31,260
Four. Three.

1604
01:05:31,327 --> 01:05:32,895
-What happened?
-Two.

1605
01:05:32,962 --> 01:05:33,963
One.

1606
01:05:34,530 --> 01:05:35,698
CLEAN

1607
01:05:35,765 --> 01:05:36,866
-He's done.
-Hit the bell.

1608
01:05:36,933 --> 01:05:38,668
Chef Sung-jun is done.

1609
01:05:38,734 --> 01:05:40,436
Did you just throw that in?

1610
01:05:40,503 --> 01:05:42,038
He couldn't top it with the cheese tuile.

1611
01:05:42,104 --> 01:05:44,774
See?
It was because of the crooked name tag.

1612
01:05:44,840 --> 01:05:47,243
-The name tag's curse.
-It ended up happening.

1613
01:05:47,310 --> 01:05:48,311
ANOTHER CROOKED NAME TAG

1614
01:05:48,377 --> 01:05:51,180
-Good work.
-He couldn't top this on the risotto.

1615
01:05:51,247 --> 01:05:52,882
That's not very important.

1616
01:05:52,949 --> 01:05:55,051
-What about that? You couldn't use it.
-It's okay.

1617
01:05:55,117 --> 01:05:57,053
The problem is this.
What if it's not cooked?

1618
01:05:58,621 --> 01:05:59,789
It takes a while to cook.

1619
01:06:03,926 --> 01:06:07,029
It wasn't easy
for Joong-ki to bring his fridge here.

1620
01:06:07,096 --> 01:06:09,198
But he may end up going home
after only eating uncooked rice.

1621
01:06:09,265 --> 01:06:11,701
Also, one of the two

1622
01:06:11,767 --> 01:06:14,470
made that tuile,

1623
01:06:14,537 --> 01:06:15,838
but he didn't use it.

1624
01:06:15,905 --> 01:06:17,173
What do you mean?

1625
01:06:18,407 --> 01:06:20,376
I mean this one.

1626
01:06:20,443 --> 01:06:22,945
It's called tuile,
something made like parched rice.

1627
01:06:23,012 --> 01:06:25,081
It was my snack.

1628
01:06:25,147 --> 01:06:26,349
He's very brazen.

1629
01:06:26,415 --> 01:06:28,050
EVERYONE IS ASTONISHED
AT HIS BRAZEN WORDS

1630
01:06:28,117 --> 01:06:30,052
YOU'RE THE BEST

1631
01:06:30,119 --> 01:06:33,289
I heard you say something
after you were done.

1632
01:06:34,523 --> 01:06:36,058
I said, "It looks so delicious."

1633
01:06:37,360 --> 01:06:38,461
He's fooling himself.

1634
01:06:38,527 --> 01:06:39,628
It takes a while to cook.

1635
01:06:40,863 --> 01:06:42,498
What was the 15-minute cook-off like?

1636
01:06:44,967 --> 01:06:46,335
I want to go home.

1637
01:06:46,902 --> 01:06:48,270
EVERYONE FEELS THE SAME

1638
01:06:48,337 --> 01:06:50,639
-Yes, it's hard.
-It is.

1639
01:06:50,706 --> 01:06:51,707
It's so hard.

1640
01:06:51,774 --> 01:06:52,808
Is it?

1641
01:06:54,110 --> 01:06:58,080
RISOTTO MADE WITH
A GENEROUS AMOUNT OF OLIVE OIL

1642
01:06:59,648 --> 01:07:04,286
ITALIAN-STYLE LENTIL SOUP
AND BEEF WITH TUNA SAUCE

1643
01:07:05,221 --> 01:07:07,890
CHEF SAM KIM'S VINSAMZO RISOTTO

1644
01:07:07,957 --> 01:07:09,392
Before the risotto…

1645
01:07:09,458 --> 01:07:11,293
This one has to taste good.

1646
01:07:11,360 --> 01:07:12,828
Lentils are very healthy for you.

1647
01:07:12,895 --> 01:07:14,764
-Yes, they are.
-Yes.

1648
01:07:14,830 --> 01:07:18,134
Hee-jun is also staring with curious eyes.

1649
01:07:18,200 --> 01:07:21,704
You'll live for a long time
by eating these healthy dishes.

1650
01:07:23,172 --> 01:07:24,540
A THUMB UP

1651
01:07:24,607 --> 01:07:26,609
-He responds right away.
-Yes.

1652
01:07:26,675 --> 01:07:28,644
The thumb went up
even before he swallowed.

1653
01:07:28,711 --> 01:07:31,614
It's so nutty. It's…

1654
01:07:31,680 --> 01:07:33,916
I see. Tomato.

1655
01:07:35,051 --> 01:07:37,787
It must be a heartwarming taste. Right?

1656
01:07:38,754 --> 01:07:40,022
It'll taste homey.

1657
01:07:40,089 --> 01:07:43,759
During the break,
I was asked to say things in Italian.

1658
01:07:43,826 --> 01:07:45,694
I said I felt too shy to do that, but…

1659
01:07:46,395 --> 01:07:47,396
<i>Delizioso.</i>

1660
01:07:48,864 --> 01:07:52,334
He's starting to speak Italian
now that he's eating Italian cuisine.

1661
01:07:52,401 --> 01:07:53,836
Yes, you're right.

1662
01:07:53,903 --> 01:07:55,004
I'll try this one.

1663
01:07:55,071 --> 01:07:56,939
It looks very light and delicious.

1664
01:07:57,006 --> 01:07:58,574
It was parboiled, so yes.

1665
01:07:58,641 --> 01:08:01,143
I used tuna, olive oil, and eggs.

1666
01:08:01,210 --> 01:08:03,145
I'll eat it with lots of sauce.

1667
01:08:04,513 --> 01:08:06,916
-We were too concerned about risotto.
-Yes.

1668
01:08:08,384 --> 01:08:10,886
LIPS GETTING DRY

1669
01:08:12,455 --> 01:08:14,423
<i>Tutto bene.</i>

1670
01:08:14,990 --> 01:08:18,127
HE BLURTS OUT MORE ITALIAN WORDS

1671
01:08:18,194 --> 01:08:19,228
Did you understand?

1672
01:08:19,295 --> 01:08:20,362
It means delicious.

1673
01:08:21,497 --> 01:08:23,466
Everything was delicious.

1674
01:08:23,532 --> 01:08:26,769
Now, Vinsamzo Risotto.

1675
01:08:27,570 --> 01:08:29,738
He made it in just 14 minutes.
Is it cooked?

1676
01:08:29,805 --> 01:08:31,140
DID THE RICE COOK IN 15 MINUTES?

1677
01:08:32,241 --> 01:08:35,244
Now, will it be Vinsamzo? Or Vinsam-flop?

1678
01:08:35,845 --> 01:08:37,847
GIGGLING

1679
01:08:38,347 --> 01:08:40,182
Is it <i>al dente</i> or is it still raw?

1680
01:08:40,249 --> 01:08:42,218
You have to tell us honestly.

1681
01:08:42,284 --> 01:08:44,120
Is it <i>al dente</i> or is it still raw?

1682
01:08:44,186 --> 01:08:46,155
You have to tell us honestly.

1683
01:08:46,222 --> 01:08:48,357
-It's <i>al dente</i>.
-It's <i>al dente</i>!

1684
01:08:48,424 --> 01:08:51,026
-It's <i>al dente</i>.
-It's <i>al dente</i>!

1685
01:08:51,093 --> 01:08:53,496
IT WAS AL DENTE

1686
01:08:53,562 --> 01:08:54,830
Sam Kim did it.

1687
01:08:54,897 --> 01:08:57,800
I stir-fried it quickly
over high heat in the beginning.

1688
01:08:57,867 --> 01:08:58,868
-In the beginning.
-In the beginning.

1689
01:08:58,934 --> 01:08:59,935
This is so good.

1690
01:09:00,002 --> 01:09:02,238
Then I added broth
and kept cooking over low heat.

1691
01:09:02,304 --> 01:09:04,006
You have to cook it over low heat?

1692
01:09:04,073 --> 01:09:05,374
-Yes.
-I see.

1693
01:09:06,408 --> 01:09:10,079
It looks like you poured
a generous amount of olive oil at the end.

1694
01:09:10,145 --> 01:09:11,147
You're right.

1695
01:09:11,213 --> 01:09:13,015
I could smell it easily.

1696
01:09:13,616 --> 01:09:15,818
<i>-Tutto bene.</i>
<i>-Tutto bene.</i>

1697
01:09:15,885 --> 01:09:17,353
-It means it's delicious.
-It does.

1698
01:09:17,419 --> 01:09:18,687
AN AWFUL IMPERSONATION

1699
01:09:18,754 --> 01:09:20,189
<i>Fantastico.</i>

1700
01:09:20,923 --> 01:09:23,659
A NEW KIND OF RISOTTO
MADE WITH BUCKWHEAT PASTA

1701
01:09:24,160 --> 01:09:26,929
DESSERT MADE
WITH RASPBERRY CHOCOLATE

1702
01:09:27,763 --> 01:09:30,666
CHEF KWON SUNG-JUN'S MATFIA RISOTTO

1703
01:09:31,233 --> 01:09:32,735
I hope it's cooked well.

1704
01:09:32,801 --> 01:09:34,003
It smells wonderful.

1705
01:09:34,069 --> 01:09:36,272
-First off, it smells great.
-It smells great.

1706
01:09:36,338 --> 01:09:39,842
It just needs to be cooked well.

1707
01:09:39,909 --> 01:09:44,313
It's the ambitious 15-minute risotto
made by Chef Sung-jun!

1708
01:09:44,380 --> 01:09:45,748
Matfia Risotto.

1709
01:09:45,814 --> 01:09:47,283
Does it taste like Mafia?

1710
01:09:47,349 --> 01:09:49,518
Or was it just a thug?

1711
01:09:50,519 --> 01:09:51,921
Be honest with us!

1712
01:09:52,721 --> 01:09:54,323
This is also <i>al dente</i>.

1713
01:09:55,591 --> 01:09:57,293
This is also <i>al dente</i>.

1714
01:09:57,359 --> 01:09:59,795
BOTH RISOTTOS ARE AL DENTE!

1715
01:09:59,862 --> 01:10:03,666
-Chef Sung-jun did it.
-It got cooked after just two minutes.

1716
01:10:03,732 --> 01:10:07,002
I was kind of sure
that it wouldn't be cooked.

1717
01:10:07,069 --> 01:10:09,471
He did wrap up in a hurry too.

1718
01:10:09,538 --> 01:10:10,773
I don't know a lot about cooking,

1719
01:10:10,839 --> 01:10:13,742
-but it's seriously cooked.
-Seriously cooked.

1720
01:10:13,809 --> 01:10:15,711
KEEPING A STRAIGHT FACE

1721
01:10:15,778 --> 01:10:19,515
It still feels soft like liquid too.

1722
01:10:19,582 --> 01:10:23,385
It's very delicious.
Also, I love to add ketchup to everything,

1723
01:10:23,452 --> 01:10:25,888
-so I like the smell of ketchup.
-The ketchup?

1724
01:10:25,955 --> 01:10:27,856
It made you enjoy it more.

1725
01:10:27,923 --> 01:10:30,826
There's no Italian
who'll throw in ketchup to pasta.

1726
01:10:30,893 --> 01:10:32,394
They never use it.

1727
01:10:32,461 --> 01:10:34,230
It makes no sense.

1728
01:10:34,296 --> 01:10:36,699
Chef Sam says it makes no sense.

1729
01:10:36,765 --> 01:10:37,766
<i>Mamma mia!</i>

1730
01:10:37,833 --> 01:10:39,268
Chef Sam couldn't hold back
and had to say that.

1731
01:10:39,335 --> 01:10:40,869
INHALING

1732
01:10:40,936 --> 01:10:43,272
-But we're in Korea.
-"But we're in Korea."

1733
01:10:43,339 --> 01:10:46,008
-We aren't in Italy.
-It's <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>.

1734
01:10:46,075 --> 01:10:50,145
That's the dessert,
raspberry chocolate pie.

1735
01:10:50,212 --> 01:10:51,513
How did you know what I liked?

1736
01:10:51,580 --> 01:10:54,049
When I live in Italy,
my wife and I always take a walk

1737
01:10:54,116 --> 01:10:56,518
with our child in the morning

1738
01:10:56,585 --> 01:10:58,921
and always eat raspberry croissants.

1739
01:10:59,488 --> 01:11:01,390
HE CAPTURED HIS TASTE

1740
01:11:01,457 --> 01:11:05,060
He's starting to become
more and more arrogant as he nods.

1741
01:11:05,127 --> 01:11:07,129
He's just Mafia, not Matfia, right?

1742
01:11:07,196 --> 01:11:09,465
-He knows everything.
-He does.

1743
01:11:09,531 --> 01:11:11,767
Everything is working out for Sung-jun.

1744
01:11:11,834 --> 01:11:12,968
-What's this?
-What is it?

1745
01:11:13,035 --> 01:11:14,603
He's trying the dessert.

1746
01:11:15,904 --> 01:11:17,206
Is it cooked all the way?

1747
01:11:18,707 --> 01:11:21,844
I wonder how greasy it is.

1748
01:11:21,910 --> 01:11:23,145
Everything is melty.

1749
01:11:23,212 --> 01:11:25,080
Really? Then it must be cooked.

1750
01:11:25,881 --> 01:11:27,950
It tastes insane.

1751
01:11:30,185 --> 01:11:31,253
-"It tastes insane."
-"It tastes insane."

1752
01:11:31,320 --> 01:11:33,622
Sung-jun is shooting at everyone.

1753
01:11:33,689 --> 01:11:35,691
He's shooting.

1754
01:11:35,758 --> 01:11:38,227
-Didn't he say he wanted to go home?
-Right?

1755
01:11:38,294 --> 01:11:41,230
He had lost his spirit before,
then he came back strong.

1756
01:11:41,297 --> 01:11:43,232
His shoulders are
about to touch the ceiling.

1757
01:11:43,299 --> 01:11:45,067
-I can't help but say this.
-Say what?

1758
01:11:45,134 --> 01:11:47,936
<i>-Mamma mia.</i>
<i>-Mamma mia.</i>

1759
01:11:49,171 --> 01:11:50,472
EXCITED

1760
01:11:50,539 --> 01:11:52,174
Kwon Sung-jun.

1761
01:11:52,241 --> 01:11:54,376
Where did the pecans go?

1762
01:11:54,443 --> 01:11:55,577
They're here.

1763
01:11:56,078 --> 01:11:57,479
Where did it go?

1764
01:11:57,546 --> 01:11:59,348
Oh, I forgot to sprinkle it.

1765
01:12:01,250 --> 01:12:04,620
-Why did you grind those?
-You didn't even say it.

1766
01:12:04,687 --> 01:12:05,754
You couldn't taste it, right?

1767
01:12:05,821 --> 01:12:08,223
-No, so I got curious.
-Yes.

1768
01:12:08,290 --> 01:12:10,225
But it's not that important.

1769
01:12:10,292 --> 01:12:12,394
HE'S SO BRAZEN

1770
01:12:12,461 --> 01:12:15,097
Let's try Chef Sam's dishes.

1771
01:12:15,164 --> 01:12:17,333
I think I'll like the taste of this.

1772
01:12:17,833 --> 01:12:20,703
-Hee-jun will live for a long time.
-It has lentils in it.

1773
01:12:21,437 --> 01:12:22,638
-You'll like that.
-I think so too.

1774
01:12:22,705 --> 01:12:23,806
A HEALTHY TASTE,
JUST HOW HE LIKES IT

1775
01:12:23,872 --> 01:12:26,375
That passed right away.

1776
01:12:26,442 --> 01:12:27,609
Anyone would like it.

1777
01:12:27,676 --> 01:12:29,611
The tuna and egg sauce.

1778
01:12:31,413 --> 01:12:32,414
What about this one?

1779
01:12:33,515 --> 01:12:35,851
-It's so good.
-He says it's so good.

1780
01:12:35,918 --> 01:12:37,886
-Lastly, the risotto.
-The risotto.

1781
01:12:37,953 --> 01:12:39,521
Chef Sam's risotto.

1782
01:12:39,588 --> 01:12:43,058
-He doesn't like anything <i>al dente</i>.
-I don't.

1783
01:12:43,125 --> 01:12:45,160
He doesn't even like things <i>al dente</i>.

1784
01:12:45,227 --> 01:12:46,895
It seems hard, but it's not irritating.

1785
01:12:49,832 --> 01:12:50,866
EYES WIDE OPEN!

1786
01:12:50,933 --> 01:12:52,267
What's wrong? Were you bothered?

1787
01:12:52,334 --> 01:12:54,436
See? I'm telling you. Right?

1788
01:12:54,503 --> 01:12:56,972
-It's hard, but it's not irritating.
-Right?

1789
01:12:57,039 --> 01:13:00,642
I've only had risotto at Pizza Hut.

1790
01:13:00,709 --> 01:13:03,412
-A place for the family.
-Yes, only there.

1791
01:13:03,479 --> 01:13:05,047
Gosh, this is great.

1792
01:13:05,114 --> 01:13:06,248
HE'S SERIOUSLY AMAZED

1793
01:13:06,315 --> 01:13:09,551
This time, it's Chef Sung-jun's risotto.

1794
01:13:09,618 --> 01:13:11,253
CHEF SUNG-JUN'S MATFIA RISOTTO

1795
01:13:11,320 --> 01:13:14,189
A dish by Chef Sung-jun.

1796
01:13:16,425 --> 01:13:18,861
What does that face mean?

1797
01:13:18,927 --> 01:13:20,429
It smells kind of unique.

1798
01:13:20,496 --> 01:13:22,231
The smell must bother him.

1799
01:13:22,297 --> 01:13:25,067
I prefer this one.

1800
01:13:25,134 --> 01:13:27,803
He prefers Chef Sam's risotto.

1801
01:13:28,604 --> 01:13:30,272
The dessert is like a pie.

1802
01:13:30,339 --> 01:13:31,507
-It must be hot.
-It's hot.

1803
01:13:32,241 --> 01:13:33,242
SAVORING

1804
01:13:34,243 --> 01:13:36,111
-Chef Sung-jun's dish.
-Whoa.

1805
01:13:37,212 --> 01:13:38,580
He's good at making dessert.

1806
01:13:39,815 --> 01:13:41,550
That man is good at dessert.

1807
01:13:41,617 --> 01:13:43,852
-Not the meal, but the dessert.
-The dessert.

1808
01:13:43,919 --> 01:13:46,522
The raspberry filling tastes similar

1809
01:13:46,588 --> 01:13:49,024
to the inside of a
famous sweet rice doughnut.

1810
01:13:49,091 --> 01:13:51,693
Raspberry filling
inside sweet rice doughnut.

1811
01:13:51,760 --> 01:13:52,995
SAVORING

1812
01:13:53,562 --> 01:13:55,831
IT'S OBVIOUS WHEN HE LIKES IT

1813
01:13:55,898 --> 01:13:56,899
He makes nasal sounds.

1814
01:13:56,965 --> 01:14:00,135
Well, now, he has to make a decision.

1815
01:14:00,202 --> 01:14:02,004
Gosh, what do I do?

1816
01:14:02,070 --> 01:14:04,840
Joong-ki is about to make
a very important decision.

1817
01:14:04,907 --> 01:14:07,843
It'll have a huge impact
in the Italian cuisine industry.

1818
01:14:09,211 --> 01:14:11,280
He gets up for another taste.

1819
01:14:12,047 --> 01:14:14,516
He needs to see if his decision is right.

1820
01:14:14,583 --> 01:14:17,386
-He has to taste the risotto.
-He's cautious.

1821
01:14:17,453 --> 01:14:18,554
He's cautious about this.

1822
01:14:18,620 --> 01:14:21,523
Will Chef Sung-jun dominate the industry?

1823
01:14:21,590 --> 01:14:25,227
If Chef Sam wins, it means he won
against everyone in <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>.

1824
01:14:25,294 --> 01:14:26,295
-Exactly.
-Yes.

1825
01:14:26,361 --> 01:14:27,529
TASTING CHEF SAM'S RISOTTO AGAIN

1826
01:14:27,596 --> 01:14:30,165
To one, it'll be a great honor.

1827
01:14:30,232 --> 01:14:31,900
To another, it'll be a huge blow.

1828
01:14:31,967 --> 01:14:33,135
THE RE-TASTING MAKES THEM NERVOUS

1829
01:14:33,802 --> 01:14:35,804
Okay, Joong-ki.

1830
01:14:35,871 --> 01:14:37,706
HE LOOKS TROUBLED

1831
01:14:37,773 --> 01:14:39,475
He's in deep thought.

1832
01:14:39,541 --> 01:14:41,143
Gosh, I'm sweating.

1833
01:14:41,210 --> 01:14:44,246
I thought my honesty would be
the best way to show my respect.

1834
01:14:44,313 --> 01:14:46,048
-Yes.
-You're right.

1835
01:14:46,114 --> 01:14:47,716
-I made my decision.
-Okay!

1836
01:14:49,218 --> 01:14:53,455
The best Italian chefs had
a risotto cook-off.

1837
01:14:54,022 --> 01:14:56,325
Will it be Saint Sam's risotto?

1838
01:14:56,391 --> 01:14:59,661
Or will it be Kwon Sung-jun
of <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>?

1839
01:14:59,728 --> 01:15:01,296
They're 18 years apart in age.

1840
01:15:02,130 --> 01:15:04,433
Sam Kim. Kwon Sung-jun.

1841
01:15:04,500 --> 01:15:06,201
Who will Joong-ki choose?

1842
01:15:06,768 --> 01:15:07,970
Which one is it?

1843
01:15:08,036 --> 01:15:10,172
The winner is…

1844
01:15:10,739 --> 01:15:13,075
WHO DID SONG JOONG-KI CHOOSE?

1845
01:15:13,141 --> 01:15:14,309
The winner is…

1846
01:15:15,544 --> 01:15:17,980
CHEF SAM'S VINSAMZO RISOTTO WINS

1847
01:15:18,046 --> 01:15:19,047
Chef Sam!

1848
01:15:20,182 --> 01:15:23,452
Sam wins against Kwon Sung-jun!

1849
01:15:24,720 --> 01:15:27,155
Chef Sam wins against Chef Sung-jun.

1850
01:15:27,222 --> 01:15:31,193
I tried my best to focus on the risotto,

1851
01:15:31,260 --> 01:15:34,196
but sadly, it seemed like Chef Sung-jun

1852
01:15:34,263 --> 01:15:36,565
couldn't stick to the plan
and had forgotten something.

1853
01:15:36,632 --> 01:15:41,236
Also, his dessert was much more delicious,

1854
01:15:41,303 --> 01:15:42,838
even more so than the main dish.

1855
01:15:42,905 --> 01:15:46,575
But Chef Sam's other dishes

1856
01:15:46,642 --> 01:15:50,712
did not interfere with the risotto.

1857
01:15:51,413 --> 01:15:53,382
The other two were a bit more simple.

1858
01:15:53,448 --> 01:15:56,251
That was how I made my decision.

1859
01:15:56,318 --> 01:15:59,454
Of course, I admit my defeat.

1860
01:15:59,521 --> 01:16:03,025
Well, I joked around a little
to make this more interesting,

1861
01:16:03,091 --> 01:16:06,828
but he was a chef
I had looked up to when I began.

1862
01:16:06,895 --> 01:16:07,896
Thank you.

1863
01:16:07,963 --> 01:16:10,465
I had a lot of fun
as I had the honor of cooking with him.

1864
01:16:10,532 --> 01:16:13,669
I'll come even more prepared next time
and win the battle.

1865
01:16:13,735 --> 01:16:16,672
I'm so glad I decided to be on the show.

1866
01:16:16,738 --> 01:16:21,143
I'll also tell my actor friends to be here
if they get an offer to.

1867
01:16:21,843 --> 01:16:23,312
Thank you.

1868
01:16:23,378 --> 01:16:26,081
Chef Sam takes his first victory!

1869
01:16:26,148 --> 01:16:27,683
-Congratulations!
-Congratulations!

1870
01:16:28,383 --> 01:16:29,618
Congratulations, Sam.

1871
01:16:29,685 --> 01:16:31,186
Please welcome today's fridge owners!

1872
01:16:33,188 --> 01:16:34,723
The ladies Gen Z look up to,

1873
01:16:34,790 --> 01:16:36,258
Jang Won-young and Lee Eun-ji!

1874
01:16:36,959 --> 01:16:38,493
May I have your autograph?

1875
01:16:39,161 --> 01:16:41,029
I was told to get your autograph.

1876
01:16:41,096 --> 01:16:42,230
She's so good at self-management.

1877
01:16:42,297 --> 01:16:43,565
We present Won-young's fridge!

1878
01:16:43,632 --> 01:16:44,700
What's that?

1879
01:16:44,766 --> 01:16:46,435
I eat that almost every day.

1880
01:16:46,501 --> 01:16:48,570
I've never recommended it to anyone.

1881
01:16:48,637 --> 01:16:49,771
-Was this the first time?
-Yes.

1882
01:16:49,838 --> 01:16:51,773
Don't you think it'll be sold out?

1883
01:16:51,840 --> 01:16:52,908
That means I'm lucky Vicky.

1884
01:16:52,975 --> 01:16:53,976
THAT MEANS I'M LUCKY VICKY

1885
01:16:54,042 --> 01:16:57,312
<i>The first and only chef in Korea</i>
<i>who has two one-star Michelin restaurants.</i>

1886
01:16:57,379 --> 01:16:59,514
<i>-Chef Son Jong-won.</i>
<i>-It's great to meet you.</i>

1887
01:16:59,581 --> 01:17:02,184
<i>-It looks so good.</i>
<i>-Please do your best until the end!</i>

1888
01:17:02,250 --> 01:17:03,251
I love you!

1889
01:17:03,318 --> 01:17:04,953
OH, MOTHER

1890
01:17:05,020 --> 01:17:07,923
<i>Who'll be the little Choi Hyun-suk?</i>
<i>And who'll be the old Matfia?</i>

1891
01:17:07,990 --> 01:17:09,725
<i>The Show-off Chef cook-off.</i>

1892
01:17:09,791 --> 01:17:11,159
That's something I love!

1893
01:17:11,226 --> 01:17:13,261
-She loves it, but they're overusing it.
-I love that!

1894
01:17:13,328 --> 01:17:15,764
-Won-young eats so well.
-It looks good.

1895
01:17:15,831 --> 01:17:16,965
A TASTE THAT MAKES HER GIVE HEARTS

1896
01:17:17,032 --> 01:17:18,867
Which one did you like more?

1897
01:17:18,934 --> 01:17:20,569
Who did Won-young choose?

1898
01:17:31,413 --> 01:17:36,418
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
